   3, 'The simplified approach — required for trade receivables without a significant financing component — always measures the allowance at lifetime expected credit losses, avoiding the need to track significant increases in credit risk.', 2),
  ('FAR', 'Receivables',
   'Customers'' accounts with credit balances at the reporting date (e.g., from overpayments or returns after payment) are:',
   'Reported as current liabilities', 'Netted against accounts receivable with debit balances', 'Ignored if individually immaterial', 'Reported as contra-assets',
   0, 'Credit balances in customers'' accounts represent obligations to deliver goods or refund cash, so they are reclassified and presented as current liabilities. Netting against other customers'' debit balances is improper offsetting.', 1),
  ('FAR', 'Receivables',
   'Under the net method of recording credit sales, sales discounts forfeited by customers who pay after the discount period are:',
   'Credited to sales revenue', 'Credited to accounts receivable', 'Recognized as other income', 'Ignored',
