   'P200,000', 'P250,000', 'P300,000', 'P400,000',
   2, 'SYD denominator = 4+3+2+1 = 10. Depreciable amount = P1,000,000. Year 2 uses the fraction 3/10: P1,000,000 × 3/10 = P300,000 (Year 1 was 4/10 = P400,000).', 2),
  ('FAR', 'Property, Plant & Equipment',
   'A machine costing P5,000,000 with a residual value of P500,000 is expected to produce 1,000,000 units over its life. It produced 150,000 units this year. Depreciation under the units-of-production method is:',
   'P600,000', 'P675,000', 'P750,000', 'P825,000',
   1, 'Depreciation rate = (P5,000,000 − P500,000) ÷ 1,000,000 = P4.50 per unit. Charge for the year = 150,000 × P4.50 = P675,000.', 2),
  ('FAR', 'Property, Plant & Equipment',
   'Under PAS 16, each part of an item of PPE with a cost that is significant in relation to the total cost of the item (e.g., an aircraft''s engines and airframe):',
   'Shall be depreciated separately', 'Shall be depreciated using the rate applicable to the principal asset', 'May be expensed when replaced', 'Shall be combined and depreciated over the average useful life',
   0, 'Component (parts) depreciation is mandatory: significant parts with different useful lives or patterns of consumption are depreciated separately, and replacements are capitalized with the replaced part derecognized.', 1),
  ('FAR', 'Property, Plant & Equipment',
   'Equipment costing P3,000,000 with no residual value was being depreciated over 10 years. At the start of Year 5, the remaining useful life was revised to 4 years. Depreciation for Year 5 is:',
   'P300,000', 'P360,000', 'P450,000', 'P600,000',
   2, 'Carrying amount after 4 years = P3,000,000 − (4 × P300,000) = P1,800,000. The change in estimate is applied prospectively: P1,800,000 ÷ 4 remaining years = P450,000 per year.', 2),
  ('FAR', 'Property, Plant & Equipment',
   'Which of the following is classified as a land improvement rather than land?',
   'Special assessments for public improvements levied by the local government', 'Cost of clearing and grading prior to construction', 'Legal fees and title insurance on acquisition', 'Cost of driveways, fences and parking lots',
   3, 'Driveways, fences, parking lots and similar depreciable additions are land improvements. Special assessments, clearing/grading incident to acquisition, and title costs attach to the land account, which is not depreciated.', 1),
  ('FAR', 'Property, Plant & Equipment',
   'A ship requires a dry-dock overhaul every three years as a condition of continued operation. The cost of each overhaul is:',
   'Expensed when paid', 'Capitalized as part of the ship''s carrying amount and depreciated over three years, derecognizing any remaining cost of the previous overhaul', 'Accrued as a provision evenly over the three years preceding the overhaul', 'Charged directly to retained earnings',
   1, 'Major inspections and overhauls are accounted for as a separate component: capitalized when performed and depreciated until the next overhaul, with any carrying amount of the previous inspection derecognized. Accruing in advance is prohibited because there is no present obligation.', 2),
  ('FAR', 'Property, Plant & Equipment',
   'Equipment with a cost of P2,400,000 and accumulated depreciation of P1,500,000 was sold for P1,100,000. The disposal results in:',
   'A gain of P200,000', 'A loss of P200,000', 'A gain of P900,000', 'A gain of P1,100,000',
   0, 'Carrying amount = P2,400,000 − P1,500,000 = P900,000. Proceeds of P1,100,000 less carrying amount of P900,000 = P200,000 gain, presented in profit or loss (not as revenue).', 1),
  ('FAR', 'Property, Plant & Equipment',
   'In an exchange of assets that lacks commercial substance, the asset received is measured at:',
   'Fair value of the asset received', 'Fair value of the asset given up', 'Carrying amount of the asset given up, with no gain or loss recognized', 'The lower of fair value and carrying amount, with a loss recognized',
   2, 'When an exchange lacks commercial substance (or fair values are not reliably measurable), the acquired asset is measured at the carrying amount of the asset surrendered, plus cash paid, and no gain or loss arises.', 2),
  ('FAR', 'Property, Plant & Equipment',
   'Under PAS 36, the recoverable amount of an asset is:',
   'Fair value less costs of disposal in all cases', 'The higher of fair value less costs of disposal and value in use', 'The lower of carrying amount and fair value', 'The present value of future cash flows in all cases',
   1, 'Recoverable amount is the higher of (1) fair value less costs of disposal and (2) value in use. An impairment loss exists only when carrying amount exceeds this recoverable amount.', 1),
  ('FAR', 'Property, Plant & Equipment',
   'An asset has a carrying amount of P4,000,000, a fair value less costs of disposal of P3,400,000, and a value in use of P3,600,000. The impairment loss is:',
   'P0', 'P400,000', 'P600,000', 'P1,000,000',
   1, 'Recoverable amount = higher of P3,400,000 and P3,600,000 = P3,600,000. Impairment loss = P4,000,000 − P3,600,000 = P400,000. Using fair value less costs of disposal alone would overstate the loss.', 2),
  ('FAR', 'Property, Plant & Equipment',
   'The reversal of an impairment loss on an asset other than goodwill is limited to:',
   'The original impairment loss recognized', 'The asset''s recoverable amount, without limit', 'The asset''s fair value at the reversal date', 'The carrying amount that would have been determined, net of depreciation, had no impairment been recognized',
   3, 'A reversal cannot lift the asset above its ''depreciated historical cost ceiling'' — the carrying amount it would have had if no impairment had ever been recognized. Goodwill impairment is never reversed.', 3),
