   3, 'The Civil Code priority is: creditors other than partners first, then partners'' loans, then return of capital, and finally partners'' profits.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Partnership Accounting',
   'Dom is admitted to the partnership of Ela and Fia, whose combined capital is P1,000,000, by investing P400,000 for a 25% interest. The partners agree to use the asset revaluation approach. The upward revaluation credited to the old partners is:',
   'P50,000', 'P100,000', 'P150,000', 'P200,000',
   3, 'Dom''s P400,000 for 25% implies total capital of P1,600,000. Contributed capital is only P1,400,000, so assets are revalued upward by P200,000, credited to Ela and Fia.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Partnership Accounting',
   'A partner''s capital was P300,000 on January 1. He invested an additional P120,000 on July 1 and withdrew P60,000 on October 1. The partnership pays 8% interest on weighted average capital. His interest allowance for the year is:',
   'P24,000', 'P26,400', 'P27,600', 'P28,800',
   2, 'Weighted average capital = P300,000 + (P120,000 × 6/12) − (P60,000 × 3/12) = P345,000. Interest = P345,000 × 8% = P27,600.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Partnership Accounting',
   'The partnership agreement is silent on how profits are to be divided among the capitalist partners. Under the Philippine Civil Code, profits should be divided:',
   'Equally among all partners', 'Based on the time each partner devoted to the business', 'Based on ending capital balances', 'In proportion to what each partner contributed',
   3, 'In the absence of an agreement, the Civil Code provides that each capitalist partner shares in profits in proportion to his contribution.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'A company in liquidation reports the following realizable values and claims: assets pledged to fully secured creditors P600,000 (claims P500,000); assets pledged to partially secured creditors P200,000 (claims P350,000); free assets P400,000; unsecured liabilities with priority P100,000; unsecured liabilities without priority P650,000. The estimated recovery percentage of unsecured creditors without priority is:',
   '44.4%', '50.0%', '61.5%', '76.9%',
   1, 'Net free assets = (P600,000 − P500,000) + P400,000 − P100,000 = P400,000. Total unsecured without priority = P650,000 + the P150,000 deficiency to partially secured creditors = P800,000. Recovery = P400,000 ÷ P800,000 = 50%.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'A creditor is owed P350,000 secured by collateral with a realizable value of P200,000. The estimated recovery percentage for unsecured claims without priority is 50%. The total amount this creditor can expect to receive is:',
   'P175,000', 'P200,000', 'P275,000', 'P350,000',
   2, 'The creditor gets the P200,000 collateral plus 50% of the P150,000 unsecured deficiency (P75,000), or P275,000 in total.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'In a statement of affairs, the realizable value of assets pledged to fully secured creditors exceeds the related claims by P100,000. This excess is:',
   'Added to free assets available to unsecured creditors', 'Retained by the secured creditor as additional protection', 'Distributed pro rata to partially secured creditors only', 'Excluded from the statement of affairs',
   0, 'Any excess of pledged collateral over a fully secured claim reverts to the estate and forms part of free assets available to unsecured creditors.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'Which of the following is classified as an unsecured liability with priority in corporate liquidation?',
   'Accounts payable to trade suppliers', 'Notes payable with no collateral', 'Unpaid employee salaries within statutory limits', 'Bonds payable secured by a mortgage on a building',
   2, 'Administrative expenses, unpaid employee salaries within limits and taxes rank as unsecured claims with priority; they are paid in full before unsecured creditors without priority receive anything.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'A liquidating corporation has free assets with a realizable value of P700,000 and unsecured liabilities with priority of P160,000. Unsecured liabilities without priority total P900,000. The estimated deficiency to unsecured creditors without priority is:',
   'P200,000', 'P360,000', 'P540,000', 'P900,000',
   1, 'Net free assets = P700,000 − P160,000 = P540,000. Deficiency = P900,000 − P540,000 = P360,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'In preparing its statement of affairs, a company shows: trade accounts payable (unsecured) of P600,000; a note payable of P350,000 secured by collateral with a realizable value of P200,000; and taxes payable of P80,000. Total unsecured liabilities without priority amount to:',
   'P600,000', 'P680,000', 'P750,000', 'P830,000',
   2, 'P600,000 trade payables + the P150,000 deficiency on the partially secured note = P750,000. Taxes are unsecured with priority and are excluded.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'Net free assets of a liquidating company are P780,000 and unsecured claims without priority total P1,200,000. A supplier with an unsecured claim of P200,000 and no collateral can expect to receive:',
   'P70,000', 'P130,000', 'P160,000', 'P200,000',
   1, 'The recovery rate is P780,000 ÷ P1,200,000 = 65%, so the supplier expects P200,000 × 65% = P130,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'In a statement of realization and liquidation, the caption assets to be realized represents:',
   'The estimated realizable value of all assets', 'The proceeds expected from future asset sales', 'Assets acquired by the trustee during the period', 'The book value of noncash assets on hand at the start of the period',
   3, 'Assets to be realized are the noncash assets at the beginning of the period stated at book value; new acquisitions appear as assets acquired and sales as assets realized.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'A statement of affairs differs from a going-concern statement of financial position primarily because assets are measured at:',
   'Historical cost less accumulated depreciation', 'Fair value less costs to sell under PFRS 5', 'General price-level adjusted amounts', 'Estimated realizable values',
   3, 'The statement of affairs is a liquidation-oriented report, so assets are shown at the amounts expected to be realized rather than at going-concern carrying amounts.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'A bank loan of P400,000 is secured by equipment with an estimated realizable value of P450,000. In the statement of affairs, the bank is classified as a:',
   'Fully secured creditor', 'Partially secured creditor', 'Unsecured creditor with priority', 'Unsecured creditor without priority',
   0, 'The collateral''s realizable value of P450,000 covers the entire P400,000 claim, so the creditor is fully secured; the P50,000 excess joins free assets.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Corporate Liquidation',
   'Free assets have a realizable value of P600,000, and assets pledged to fully secured creditors exceed the related claims by P80,000. Unsecured liabilities with priority consist of administrative expenses of P70,000, salaries of P50,000 and taxes of P60,000. Net free assets available to unsecured creditors without priority are:',
   'P420,000', 'P500,000', 'P600,000', 'P680,000',
   1, 'Total free assets = P600,000 + P80,000 excess = P680,000. Less priority claims of P180,000 gives net free assets of P500,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'Under PFRS 11, joint control exists only when:',
   'a majority of the parties agree on the relevant activities', 'one party owns more than 50% of the voting rights', 'decisions about the relevant activities require the unanimous consent of the parties sharing control', 'the arrangement is structured through a separate vehicle',
   2, 'PFRS 11 defines joint control as the contractually agreed sharing of control where decisions about the relevant activities require the unanimous consent of the parties sharing control.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'A joint arrangement that is NOT structured through a separate vehicle is classified as:',
   'a joint operation', 'a joint venture', 'an associate', 'a subsidiary',
   0, 'PFRS 11 provides that when a joint arrangement is not structured through a separate vehicle, it is always a joint operation; the parties have direct rights to the assets and obligations for the liabilities.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'In a joint operation, each joint operator recognizes in its financial statements:',
   'its share of the net assets using the equity method', 'only a single-line investment measured at fair value', 'nothing until the arrangement distributes cash', 'its share of the assets, liabilities, revenues, and expenses relating to its interest',
   3, 'A joint operator recognizes its assets, its liabilities, its revenue, and its expenses (including its share of those held or incurred jointly) in accordance with the applicable PFRSs.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'Under current PFRS 11, a joint venturer accounts for its interest in a joint venture using:',
   'proportionate consolidation', 'the cost method', 'the equity method', 'fair value through profit or loss only',
   2, 'A joint venturer recognizes its interest as an investment accounted for using the equity method under PAS 28; proportionate consolidation is no longer permitted.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'The classification of a joint arrangement structured through a separate vehicle depends on all of the following EXCEPT:',
   'the legal form of the separate vehicle', 'the terms of the contractual arrangement', 'the relative percentage ownership of each party considered in isolation', 'other facts and circumstances',
   2, 'Classification depends on the legal form, the contractual terms, and other facts and circumstances; relative ownership percentage alone is not a determining factor for classification.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'Andrea contributed P5,000,000 cash for a 40% interest in JV Corp, a joint venture. In its first year, JV Corp reported profit of P3,000,000 and declared dividends of P800,000. Andrea''s carrying amount of the investment at year-end is:',
   'P5,000,000', 'P6,200,000', 'P6,520,000', 'P5,880,000',
   3, 'Equity method: P5,000,000 + (40% × P3,000,000) − (40% × P800,000) = P5,000,000 + P1,200,000 − P320,000 = P5,880,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'Bravo Inc. holds a 30% interest in a joint venture acquired for P4,000,000. The venture incurred a loss of P2,000,000 in the year. The investment balance after applying the equity method is:',
   'P3,400,000', 'P3,700,000', 'P4,000,000', 'P4,600,000',
   0, 'Equity method: P4,000,000 − (30% × P2,000,000) = P4,000,000 − P600,000 = P3,400,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'A party that participates in a joint operation but does NOT have joint control, yet has rights to the assets and obligations for the liabilities, shall:',
   'account for its interest using the equity method', 'recognize the interest at fair value under PFRS 9 only', 'not recognize any interest', 'account for its interest in the same way as a joint operator',
   3, 'Under PFRS 11, a party that participates in a joint operation without having joint control still accounts for its interest as a joint operator if it has rights to the assets and obligations for the liabilities.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'Charlie Corp acquired a 25% interest in a joint venture for P6,000,000. The venture earned P4,800,000 profit and paid P1,200,000 dividends during the year. The investment income reported by Charlie under the equity method is:',
   'P1,200,000', 'P300,000', 'P900,000', 'P1,500,000',
   0, 'Equity-method investment income equals the investor''s share of the venture''s profit: 25% × P4,800,000 = P1,200,000. Dividends reduce the carrying amount but are not income.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'Delta and Echo jointly own and operate a pipeline as a joint operation, sharing output 60:40. Total operating costs for the year were P10,000,000. Delta recognizes operating expenses of:',
   'P4,000,000', 'P5,000,000', 'P6,000,000', 'P10,000,000',
   2, 'As a joint operator, Delta recognizes its share of the jointly incurred expenses: 60% × P10,000,000 = P6,000,000.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'A party that holds an interest in a joint venture but does NOT have joint control and has no significant influence accounts for that interest under:',
   'PAS 28 using the equity method', 'PFRS 9 as a financial asset', 'PFRS 11 as a joint operator', 'proportionate consolidation',
   1, 'Without joint control or significant influence, the interest in a joint venture is accounted for as a financial asset in accordance with PFRS 9.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'Foxtrot Corp acquired a 35% interest in a joint venture for P8,000,000 on January 1. The venture reported profit of P6,000,000 for the year and declared no dividends. On December 31, the carrying amount of Foxtrot''s investment is:',
   'P8,000,000', 'P9,400,000', 'P10,100,000', 'P14,000,000',
   2, 'Equity method: P8,000,000 + (35% × P6,000,000) = P8,000,000 + P2,100,000 = P10,100,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Joint Arrangements',
   'Which statement best distinguishes a joint operation from a joint venture under PFRS 11?',
   'A joint operation always uses a separate vehicle while a joint venture never does', 'In a joint operation the parties have rights to the net assets, while in a joint venture they have rights to individual assets', 'Both are accounted for identically using the equity method', 'In a joint operation the parties have rights to the assets and obligations for the liabilities, while in a joint venture they have rights to the net assets',
   3, 'A joint operation gives the parties rights to the assets and obligations for the liabilities of the arrangement; a joint venture gives the parties rights only to the net assets of the arrangement.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Golf Co. sells goods costing P450,000 for P600,000 on the installment basis. The gross profit rate based on sales is:',
   '20%', '25%', '33.3%', '75%',
   1, 'Gross profit = P600,000 − P450,000 = P150,000. Gross profit rate on sales = P150,000 ÷ P600,000 = 25%.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Hotel Inc. had installment sales of P900,000 with a gross profit rate of 30%. Collections during the year totaled P540,000. Realized gross profit for the year is:',
   'P108,000', 'P270,000', 'P378,000', 'P162,000',
   3, 'Realized gross profit = collections × gross profit rate = P540,000 × 30% = P162,000.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'India Corp made installment sales of P1,200,000 during the year at a 40% gross profit rate. By year-end, P700,000 had been collected. The deferred gross profit balance at year-end is:',
   'P200,000', 'P280,000', 'P480,000', 'P500,000',
   0, 'Uncollected balance = P1,200,000 − P700,000 = P500,000. Deferred gross profit = P500,000 × 40% = P200,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Juliet Co. reports gross profit rates of 30% for 2024 sales and 35% for 2025 sales. In 2025, collections were P400,000 on 2024 installment receivables and P600,000 on 2025 sales. Total realized gross profit recognized in 2025 is:',
   'P120,000', 'P210,000', 'P330,000', 'P350,000',
   2, 'RGP from 2024 = P400,000 × 30% = P120,000. RGP from 2025 = P600,000 × 35% = P210,000. Total = P120,000 + P210,000 = P330,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Kilo Inc. sold merchandise on installment for P500,000 (cost P350,000). After collecting P200,000, the customer defaulted and the goods were repossessed with a fair value of P120,000. The gross profit rate is 30%. The result on repossession is a:',
   'P90,000 loss', 'P90,000 gain', 'P30,000 loss', 'P30,000 gain',
   0, 'Uncollected balance = P500,000 − P200,000 = P300,000. Unrecovered cost = P300,000 × (1 − 30%) = P210,000. Result = fair value P120,000 − unrecovered cost P210,000 = P90,000 loss.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Lima Corp uses the installment method. An installment receivable of P250,000 (gross profit rate 40%) was defaulted and merchandise was repossessed at a fair value of P170,000. The result on repossession is a:',
   'P20,000 loss', 'P20,000 gain', 'P80,000 gain', 'P100,000 loss',
   1, 'Deferred GP cancelled = P250,000 × 40% = P100,000. Unrecovered cost = P250,000 − P100,000 = P150,000. Result = fair value P170,000 − unrecovered cost P150,000 = P20,000 gain.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Mike Co. accepted a trade-in valued at P50,000 against a new item priced at P200,000, but allowed the customer a trade-in allowance of P70,000. The over-allowance is:',
   'P20,000', 'P50,000', 'P70,000', 'P130,000',
   0, 'Over-allowance = trade-in allowance granted − fair value of trade-in = P70,000 − P50,000 = P20,000, which reduces net installment sales.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'November Inc. recorded an installment sale at a list price of P300,000 and granted a trade-in allowance of P80,000 on goods with a fair value of P55,000. The adjusted (net) installment sale used to compute the gross profit rate is:',
   'P220,000', 'P245,000', 'P275,000', 'P300,000',
   2, 'Over-allowance = P80,000 − P55,000 = P25,000. Net installment sale = P300,000 − P25,000 over-allowance = P275,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'In the statement of financial position, deferred gross profit on installment sales is best presented as:',
   'an addition to installment receivables', 'a current liability separate from receivables', 'a contra-asset deducted from installment receivables', 'a component of equity',
   2, 'Deferred gross profit is reported as a contra-asset, deducted from the related installment accounts receivable, until the related collections are received.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Oscar Construction uses the cost-to-cost method to measure progress. A 3-year contract has a price of P20,000,000 and total estimated costs of P16,000,000. Costs incurred to date at the end of Year 1 are P4,000,000. The percentage of completion is:',
   '20%', '25%', '40%', '80%',
   1, 'Percentage complete = costs to date ÷ total estimated costs = P4,000,000 ÷ P16,000,000 = 25%.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Papa Builders has a P30,000,000 contract with total estimated cost of P24,000,000. At the end of Year 1, costs incurred were P9,600,000. Revenue recognized in Year 1 under the over-time (cost-to-cost) method is:',
   'P9,600,000', 'P18,000,000', 'P30,000,000', 'P12,000,000',
   3, 'Percentage complete = P9,600,000 ÷ P24,000,000 = 40%. Revenue Year 1 = 40% × P30,000,000 = P12,000,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Quebec Corp has a P25,000,000 contract, total estimated cost P20,000,000. Year 1 costs incurred were P5,000,000. The gross profit recognized in Year 1 under the cost-to-cost method is:',
   'P1,250,000', 'P6,250,000', 'P5,000,000', 'P1,000,000',
   0, 'Percentage complete = P5,000,000 ÷ P20,000,000 = 25%. Total expected gross profit = P25,000,000 − P20,000,000 = P5,000,000. Year 1 GP = 25% × P5,000,000 = P1,250,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Romeo Construction reports the following for a P40,000,000 contract: total estimated cost P32,000,000; cumulative costs of P8,000,000 at end of Year 1 and P20,000,000 at end of Year 2. The gross profit recognized in Year 2 is:',
   'P2,000,000', 'P5,000,000', 'P8,000,000', 'P3,000,000',
   3, 'Total GP = P40,000,000 − P32,000,000 = P8,000,000. End Year 1 = (8,000,000 ÷ 32,000,000) × 8,000,000 = 2,000,000 cumulative. End Year 2 = (20,000,000 ÷ 32,000,000) × 8,000,000 = 5,000,000 cumulative. Year 2 GP = 5,000,000 − 2,000,000 = 3,000,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Tango Corp uses the cost-to-cost method. A contract shows cumulative costs incurred of P14,000,000 and recognized gross profit to date of P3,000,000. The Construction in Progress (CIP) balance is:',
   'P3,000,000', 'P11,000,000', 'P14,000,000', 'P17,000,000',
   3, 'CIP = costs incurred to date + cumulative recognized gross profit = P14,000,000 + P3,000,000 = P17,000,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Uniform Builders has cumulative CIP of P22,000,000 and progress billings of P18,000,000 on an unfinished contract. The amount presented in the statement of financial position is a:',
   'contract liability of P4,000,000', 'contract asset of P4,000,000', 'contract asset of P22,000,000', 'contract liability of P18,000,000',
   1, 'When CIP exceeds billings, the excess is a contract asset: P22,000,000 − P18,000,000 = P4,000,000 contract asset.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Victor Construction has CIP of P15,000,000 and progress billings of P19,000,000 on a contract still in progress. This is reported as a:',
   'contract asset of P4,000,000', 'contract liability of P4,000,000', 'contract asset of P15,000,000', 'contract liability of P19,000,000',
   1, 'When progress billings exceed CIP, the excess is a contract liability: P19,000,000 − P15,000,000 = P4,000,000 contract liability.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Whiskey Corp cannot reliably estimate the outcome of a contract but expects to recover its costs. Costs incurred to date are P6,000,000 of an expected total of P15,000,000. Under the cost-recovery (zero-profit) approach, revenue recognized to date is:',
   'P0', 'P6,000,000', 'P9,000,000', 'P15,000,000',
   1, 'When the outcome cannot be reliably estimated but costs are recoverable, revenue is recognized only to the extent of recoverable costs incurred = P6,000,000, with zero profit.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Xray Builders signed a P28,000,000 contract. At year-end, costs incurred were P10,000,000 and estimated costs to complete were P22,000,000. The total loss to be recognized immediately is:',
   'P4,000,000', 'P0', 'P10,000,000', 'P22,000,000',
   0, 'Total estimated cost = P10,000,000 + P22,000,000 = P32,000,000. Expected total loss = P28,000,000 − P32,000,000 = P4,000,000, recognized immediately and in full.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Yankee Corp has a P60,000,000 contract with total estimated cost of P48,000,000. At end of Year 1, costs incurred were P12,000,000. Progress billings were P10,000,000 and collections were P8,000,000. The gross profit for Year 1 is:',
   'P2,000,000', 'P3,000,000', 'P12,000,000', 'P15,000,000',
   1, 'Percentage complete = P12,000,000 ÷ P48,000,000 = 25%. Total GP = P60,000,000 − P48,000,000 = P12,000,000. Year 1 GP = 25% × P12,000,000 = P3,000,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Zulu Inc. sold goods on installment for P800,000 with a cost of P560,000. Total collections for the year, including a P50,000 down payment, were P350,000. The realized gross profit is:',
   'P105,000', 'P150,000', 'P210,000', 'P240,000',
   0, 'Gross profit rate = (P800,000 − P560,000) ÷ P800,000 = 30%. Realized GP = P350,000 collected × 30% = P105,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Alpha Corp had a deferred gross profit balance of P180,000 at the start of the year, relating to installment receivables with a 36% gross profit rate. During the year, P300,000 was collected on those receivables. The deferred gross profit balance at year-end is:',
   'P180,000', 'P128,000', 'P108,000', 'P72,000',
   3, 'Beginning receivable = P180,000 ÷ 36% = P500,000. Collections P300,000 leave P200,000 uncollected. Ending deferred GP = P200,000 × 36% = P72,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Beta Builders has a single contract priced at P45,000,000 with total estimated cost of P36,000,000. By the end of Year 2, cumulative costs were P27,000,000 and Year 1 recognized gross profit was P3,000,000. The gross profit recognized in Year 2 is:',
   'P3,000,000', 'P3,750,000', 'P6,750,000', 'P9,000,000',
   1, 'Total GP = P45,000,000 − P36,000,000 = P9,000,000. Cumulative % at end Year 2 = P27,000,000 ÷ P36,000,000 = 75%. Cumulative GP = 75% × P9,000,000 = P6,750,000. Year 2 GP = P6,750,000 − P3,000,000 = P3,750,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Gamma Co. reports installment sales of P2,000,000 in 2025 with a cost of P1,300,000. Down payment plus first-year collections totaled P800,000. The deferred gross profit at the end of 2025 is:',
   'P280,000', 'P630,000', 'P700,000', 'P420,000',
   3, 'Gross profit rate = (P2,000,000 − P1,300,000) ÷ P2,000,000 = 35%. Uncollected = P2,000,000 − P800,000 = P1,200,000. Deferred GP = P1,200,000 × 35% = P420,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Iota Corp recognizes gross profit on the installment basis. Its installment receivables decreased from P900,000 to P600,000 during the year (no write-offs). With a gross profit rate of 28%, the realized gross profit for the year is:',
   'P84,000', 'P168,000', 'P252,000', 'P300,000',
   0, 'Collections = decrease in receivables = P900,000 − P600,000 = P300,000. Realized GP = P300,000 × 28% = P84,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Installment Sales & Long-Term Construction',
   'Kappa Builders incurred costs of P8,000,000 on a contract on which an overall loss of P2,000,000 is now expected. No profit was recognized previously. The provision for the anticipated loss recognized this year is:',
   'P0', 'P2,000,000', 'P8,000,000', 'P10,000,000',
   1, 'Under PFRS 15, when a contract is expected to be loss-making, the entire anticipated loss of P2,000,000 is recognized immediately and in full as an expense.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Under PFRS 15, a nonrefundable initial franchise fee is allocated to:',
   'the franchisor''s profit only', 'each distinct good or service promised in the contract based on relative stand-alone selling prices', 'continuing royalty obligations only', 'the period in which cash is received regardless of performance',
   1, 'The transaction price, including the initial franchise fee, is allocated to each distinct performance obligation based on relative stand-alone selling prices and recognized as each obligation is satisfied.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'A franchise that grants the franchisee a right to ACCESS the franchisor''s symbolic intellectual property over the franchise term is a performance obligation satisfied:',
   'at the point the franchise opens', 'at the end of the franchise term', 'over time during the franchise period', 'only when the initial fee is collected',
   2, 'A license of symbolic IP (a right to access) is satisfied over time, so the related portion of the fee is recognized over the franchise period.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Continuing franchise fees based on a percentage of the franchisee''s sales are recognized by the franchisor:',
   'entirely when the franchise agreement is signed', 'only at the end of the reporting period in equal amounts', 'as the franchisee''s related sales occur', 'when the initial franchise fee is fully amortized',
   2, 'Sales-based royalties are recognized as revenue as the underlying sales by the franchisee occur, under the royalty exception in PFRS 15.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Nile Franchising charges an initial fee of P1,500,000: P900,000 for the franchise license (right to access, over a 5-year term) and P600,000 for initial training and equipment delivered at opening. At the opening date, the revenue recognized is:',
   'P180,000', 'P600,000', 'P780,000', 'P1,500,000',
   1, 'The P600,000 for training and equipment is a distinct obligation satisfied at opening and recognized in full. The P900,000 license is recognized over 5 years, so none of it is recognized at opening.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Oasis Corp signed a franchise with an initial fee of P2,000,000 covering only a right to access its brand over a 4-year term, collected upfront. Revenue recognized in the first year is:',
   'P0', 'P500,000', 'P1,000,000', 'P2,000,000',
   1, 'A right-to-access license is satisfied over time; the P2,000,000 is recognized evenly over 4 years = P2,000,000 ÷ 4 = P500,000 per year.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Petra Inc. grants a franchise license that is a right to USE its functional intellectual property as it exists at the grant date. The license fee is recognized:',
   'over the franchise term on a straight-line basis', 'at the point in time the franchisee can use and benefit from the license', 'only as the franchisee''s sales occur', 'never, because functional IP is not a performance obligation',
   1, 'A license of functional IP (right to use) is satisfied at a point in time when the franchisee is able to use and benefit from the license.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Quartz Franchising received an initial fee of P3,000,000 allocated based on stand-alone prices: license (right to access, over 3 years) P1,800,000; equipment delivered at opening P1,200,000. The franchisee also owes a 5% royalty on sales, which were P4,000,000 in Year 1. Total revenue recognized by Quartz in Year 1 is:',
   'P600,000', 'P1,200,000', 'P2,000,000', 'P3,200,000',
   2, 'Equipment P1,200,000 at opening + license P1,800,000 ÷ 3 years = P600,000 + royalty 5% × P4,000,000 = P200,000. Total = P1,200,000 + P600,000 + P200,000 = P2,000,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Under a consignment arrangement, the consignor recognizes revenue:',
   'when the goods are shipped to the consignee', 'when the consignment agreement is signed', 'when the consignee sells the goods to the end customer', 'when the consignee acknowledges receipt of the goods',
   2, 'In a consignment, control is not transferred on shipment; the consignor recognizes revenue only when the consignee sells the goods to the end customer.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Rhine Co. consigned 100 units costing P800 each to a dealer and paid P10,000 freight to deliver all units. The dealer sold 60 units. The cost of the ending consignment inventory reported by Rhine is:',
   'P32,000', 'P36,000', 'P40,000', 'P50,000',
   1, 'Unsold units = 40. Cost per unit including freight = P800 + (P10,000 ÷ 100) = P900. Ending consignment inventory = 40 × P900 = P36,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Seine Corp consigned goods to an agent who sold them for P500,000 and is entitled to a 15% commission plus reimbursement of P12,000 advertising. The net remittance to Seine is:',
   'P413,000', 'P425,000', 'P437,000', 'P500,000',
   0, 'Commission = 15% × P500,000 = P75,000. Net remittance = P500,000 − P75,000 commission − P12,000 advertising = P413,000.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Thames Inc. shipped 200 units costing P1,500 each on consignment, paying P20,000 freight to deliver all units. The consignee sold 150 units at P2,500 each, charging a 10% commission. The consignor''s profit on the units sold is:',
   'P82,500', 'P97,500', 'P112,500', 'P135,000',
   1, 'Sales = 150 × 2,500 = 375,000. Cost of units sold including freight = 150 × (1,500 + 20,000 ÷ 200) = 150 × 1,600 = 240,000. Commission = 10% × 375,000 = 37,500. Profit = 375,000 − 240,000 − 37,500 = 97,500.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Volga Franchising sold a franchise with a P2,400,000 initial fee. P1,000,000 relates to equipment and supplies delivered at opening; the remaining P1,400,000 is for a right-to-access license over 7 years. In Year 1, revenue recognized from the license portion is:',
   'P200,000', 'P350,000', 'P1,000,000', 'P1,400,000',
   0, 'The license is a right-to-access obligation recognized over 7 years: P1,400,000 ÷ 7 = P200,000 per year.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Franchise & Consignment',
   'Ganges Corp consigned merchandise costing P300,000 to a dealer. The dealer sold 70% of it. The cost of consigned goods sold to be recognized by Ganges is:',
   'P90,000', 'P150,000', 'P210,000', 'P300,000',
