   0, 'Predetermined rate = P900,000 / 60,000 machine hours = P15.00 per machine hour.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'In process costing with the weighted-average method, equivalent units of production for a cost element equal:',
   'Units started only', 'Units completed and transferred out plus equivalent units in ending work in process', 'Units completed minus beginning WIP', 'Units in ending WIP only',
   1, 'Under weighted average, EUP = units completed and transferred out + (ending WIP x percentage complete for that element).', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'A department completed 40,000 units and had 10,000 units in ending WIP that are 100% complete as to materials (added at the start) and 30% complete as to conversion. EUP for materials (weighted average) is:',
   '40,000', '43,000', '50,000', '53,000',
   2, 'Materials are added at the start, so ending WIP is 100% complete for materials. EUP materials = 40,000 completed + 10,000 x 100% = 50,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'Using the same data (40,000 completed; 10,000 ending WIP 30% complete as to conversion), EUP for conversion (weighted average) is:',
   '40,000', '43,000', '50,000', '13,000',
   1, 'Conversion EUP = 40,000 completed + 10,000 x 30% = 40,000 + 3,000 = 43,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'Total conversion cost to account for is P860,000 and conversion EUP (weighted average) is 43,000. The conversion cost per equivalent unit is:',
   'P20.00', 'P21.50', 'P2.00', 'P18.60',
   0, 'Cost per EUP = P860,000 / 43,000 = P20.00 per equivalent unit.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'Under the FIFO method of process costing, equivalent units differ from weighted average because FIFO:',
   'Excludes the work done last period on beginning WIP (only this period work counts)', 'Includes beginning WIP units as if started this period', 'Ignores ending WIP', 'Uses standard costs',
   0, 'FIFO counts only the equivalent work performed during the current period, so it excludes the prior-period work already done on beginning WIP units.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'A department had 5,000 units in beginning WIP (60% complete as to conversion), completed 45,000 units, and had 8,000 units in ending WIP (25% complete as to conversion). Conversion EUP under FIFO is:',
   '47,000', '46,000', '44,000', '49,000',
   2, 'FIFO conversion EUP = work to finish beginning WIP 5,000 x 40% (2,000) + units started and completed (45,000 − 5,000 = 40,000) + ending WIP 8,000 x 25% (2,000) = 44,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'Spoilage that arises under efficient operating conditions and is inherent in the production process is classified as:',
   'Abnormal spoilage charged to a loss account', 'Scrap', 'Normal spoilage, generally treated as a product cost', 'Rework',
   2, 'Normal spoilage is expected under efficient conditions and is generally absorbed as a product cost; abnormal spoilage is charged to a loss in the period.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'Two joint products, X and Y, are produced from a P600,000 joint cost. Product X has 30,000 physical units and Y has 20,000 physical units. Using the physical-units method, the joint cost allocated to X is:',
   'P240,000', 'P300,000', 'P360,000', 'P200,000',
   2, 'Allocation to X = P600,000 x (30,000 / 50,000) = P600,000 x 0.60 = P360,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'Joint cost of P800,000 is allocated using relative sales value at split-off. Product A sells for P700,000 and Product B for P300,000 at split-off. Joint cost allocated to Product A is:',
   'P560,000', 'P240,000', 'P700,000', 'P400,000',
   0, 'Total sales value = P700,000 + P300,000 = P1,000,000. Allocation to A = P800,000 x (P700,000 / P1,000,000) = P560,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'Under activity-based costing, the activity rate for an activity is computed as:',
   'Total overhead divided by direct labor hours', 'Direct materials divided by units', 'Sales divided by units', 'Activity cost pool divided by the activity cost driver volume',
   3, 'An ABC activity rate = total cost in the activity cost pool / total quantity of the cost driver for that activity.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'A setup activity pool costs P450,000 with 1,500 setups expected. A product requiring 40 setups is assigned setup cost of:',
   'P12,000', 'P300', 'P18,000', 'P30,000',
   0, 'Activity rate = P450,000 / 1,500 setups = P300 per setup. Assigned to the product = 40 x P300 = P12,000.', 3),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'A by-product is typically accounted for by:',
   'Allocating a large share of joint cost to it', 'Ignoring it entirely with no records', 'Treating it as the main product', 'Recognizing its net realizable value as a reduction of the main product cost (or as other income)',
   3, 'By-products have minor value; a common method credits their net realizable value against the joint cost of the main products (or recognizes it as other income).', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'Backflush costing, often used in JIT environments, is characterized by:',
   'Detailed tracking of costs through every work-in-process stage', 'Recording overhead only at the start', 'Allocating joint costs by sales value', 'Delaying the recording of costs and flushing them out at completion or sale, with minimal WIP tracking',
   3, 'Backflush costing simplifies accounting by recording costs at trigger points (completion or sale) and minimizing detailed WIP tracking, suited to JIT with low inventories.', 2),
  ('AFAR', 'Consolidated Financial Statements',
   'Under PFRS 10, an investor controls an investee when it has all of the following EXCEPT:',
   'Power over the investee', 'Exposure to variable returns from the investee', 'The ability to use power to affect those returns', 'Ownership of at least 51% of the voting shares',
   3, 'Control under PFRS 10 requires power, exposure to variable returns, and the ability to use power to affect returns. A specific 51% threshold is not required; control can exist with less or be absent with more.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Foreign Currency Transactions & Translation',
   'Under PAS 21, a foreign currency transaction is initially recorded by applying to the foreign currency amount the:',
   'Closing rate at year-end', 'Forward rate', 'Average rate for the period', 'Spot exchange rate at the date of the transaction',
   3, 'A foreign currency transaction is recorded on initial recognition at the spot exchange rate at the transaction date.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Derivatives & Hedge Accounting',
   'Under PFRS 9, which of the following is NOT a characteristic of a derivative?',
   'Its value changes in response to an underlying', 'It requires a large initial net investment relative to other contracts', 'It requires little or no initial net investment', 'It is settled at a future date',
   1, 'A derivative requires little or no initial net investment. The other features (an underlying, future settlement) are characteristics of derivatives.', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Not-for-Profit & Government Accounting',
   'A donor contributes P500,000 to a not-for-profit with no stipulation on its use. The contribution is recognized as revenue:',
   'With donor restrictions', 'Without donor restrictions', 'As a liability', 'Only when spent',
   1, 'An unconditional contribution with no donor stipulation is recognized immediately as revenue without donor restrictions (unrestricted).', 1),
  ('AFAR', 'Cost Accounting Systems',
   'A job-order shop applies overhead at P12 per direct labor hour. Job 101 used 350 direct labor hours. Applied overhead for Job 101 is:',
   'P350', 'P4,200', 'P12', 'P3,500',
   1, 'Applied overhead = predetermined rate x actual activity = P12 x 350 hours = P4,200.', 1)
)
insert into public.questions (topic_id, stem, choices, correct_index, explanation, difficulty)
select t.id, q.stem, jsonb_build_array(q.a, q.b, q.c, q.d), q.correct_index, q.explanation, q.difficulty
from q join t on t.code = q.subject_code and lower(t.name) = lower(q.topic)
where not exists (select 1 from public.questions x where x.stem = q.stem);

-- ===== mas-batch-001 =====
-- Generated from content/mas-batch-001.csv by scripts/csv-to-seed-sql.mjs — do not edit by hand.
-- Idempotent: skips any question whose stem already exists.
with t as (
  select tp.id, tp.name, s.code from public.topics tp
  join public.subjects s on s.id = tp.subject_id
),
q(subject_code, topic, stem, a, b, c, d, correct_index, explanation, difficulty) as (values
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Which statement best describes management accounting as compared with financial accounting?',
   'It must strictly comply with Philippine Financial Reporting Standards', 'It emphasizes audited historical reports prepared for external users', 'It is required by regulators for all corporations', 'It provides relevant information to internal decision makers and need not follow PFRS',
   3, 'Management accounting serves managers inside the firm; it is optional, future-oriented, and not bound by PFRS, which governs financial reporting to external users.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Which of the following is primarily a treasurership function rather than a controllership function?',
   'Custody of cash and management of short-term investments', 'Preparation of financial statements', 'Administration of the budgeting process', 'Maintenance of accounting records and internal control over transactions',
   0, 'The treasurer is responsible for custody of funds, cash management, credit, and investments; reporting, budgeting, and record-keeping belong to the controller.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'For a furniture manufacturer, which of the following is a product cost?',
   'Advertising for the annual furniture trade fair', 'Depreciation of factory woodworking equipment', 'Commissions paid to sales agents', 'Salaries of the corporate accounting staff',
   1, 'Product costs are direct materials, direct labor, and factory overhead. Depreciation of factory equipment is factory overhead; the others are period (selling and administrative) costs.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Which cost element is included in both prime cost and conversion cost?',
   'Direct materials', 'Direct labor', 'Factory overhead', 'Selling and administrative costs',
   1, 'Prime cost = direct materials + direct labor; conversion cost = direct labor + factory overhead. Direct labor appears in both.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'A manufacturer incurred direct materials of P300,000, direct labor of P200,000, and factory overhead of P150,000 during the month. Conversion cost is:',
   'P350,000', 'P450,000', 'P500,000', 'P650,000',
   0, 'Conversion cost = direct labor + factory overhead = P200,000 + P150,000 = P350,000. P500,000 is the prime cost and P650,000 is total manufacturing cost.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Which of the following is a sunk cost in a machine-replacement decision?',
   'The book value of the old machine being replaced', 'The purchase price of the new machine', 'The future maintenance cost of the old machine if retained', 'The trade-in value offered for the old machine',
   0, 'A sunk cost is a past cost that cannot be changed by any future decision. The old machine''s book value results from a past outlay and is irrelevant; the other items are future amounts that differ between alternatives.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Opportunity cost is best defined as:',
   'A cost that was incurred in a prior period', 'A cost that requires a current cash outlay', 'The difference in total fixed costs between two alternatives', 'The benefit given up when one alternative is chosen over the next best alternative',
   3, 'Opportunity cost is the potential benefit forgone by selecting one course of action over the next best alternative; it is not recorded in the accounts but is relevant to decisions.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'For decision-making purposes, a relevant cost is:',
   'A past cost that differs among alternatives', 'A future cost that is the same across all alternatives', 'Any cost that is unavoidable', 'An expected future cost that differs between the alternatives being considered',
   3, 'To be relevant, a cost must both occur in the future and differ between alternatives. Past costs are sunk, and future costs common to all options do not affect the choice.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Total cost at 5,000 units of output is P200,000, of which P80,000 is fixed. Within the relevant range, total cost at 6,000 units is:',
   'P144,000', 'P200,000', 'P224,000', 'P240,000',
   2, 'Variable cost per unit = (P200,000 − P80,000) ÷ 5,000 = P24. Total at 6,000 units = P80,000 + (6,000 × P24) = P224,000. P240,000 wrongly treats the entire cost as variable.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'A company hires one quality inspector at a fixed monthly salary for every 1,000 units of monthly output. Over a wide range of output, total inspection salaries are best described as a:',
   'Variable cost', 'Step cost', 'Committed fixed cost', 'Purely fixed cost',
   1, 'The cost is constant within narrow 1,000-unit bands but jumps to a higher level each time another inspector is added, which is the pattern of a step cost.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Maintenance cost was P640,000 at the highest activity level of 9,000 units and P440,000 at the lowest level of 5,000 units. Using the high-low method, the variable cost per unit is:',
   'P40.00', 'P50.00', 'P71.11', 'P88.00',
   1, 'Variable rate = (P640,000 − P440,000) ÷ (9,000 − 5,000) = P200,000 ÷ 4,000 = P50 per unit. Dividing total cost by units at either level mixes in fixed costs.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Utility cost was P900,000 at 12,000 machine hours (highest level) and P700,000 at 8,000 machine hours (lowest level). Using the high-low method, total fixed cost per period is:',
   'P100,000', 'P200,000', 'P300,000', 'P500,000',
   2, 'Variable rate = (P900,000 − P700,000) ÷ (12,000 − 8,000) = P50 per hour. Fixed cost = P900,000 − (12,000 × P50) = P300,000, confirmed at the low point: P700,000 − (8,000 × P50) = P300,000.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Repair cost was P520,000 at 10,000 machine hours (highest) and P360,000 at 6,000 machine hours (lowest). Using the high-low method, the expected repair cost at 9,000 machine hours is:',
   'P360,000', 'P468,000', 'P480,000', 'P540,000',
   2, 'Variable rate = (P520,000 − P360,000) ÷ 4,000 = P40; fixed = P520,000 − (10,000 × P40) = P120,000. At 9,000 hours: P120,000 + (9,000 × P40) = P480,000.', 3),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'A least-squares regression of maintenance cost on machine hours produced a coefficient of determination of 0.81. This means that:',
   'The variable rate per machine hour is accurate 81% of the time', 'The correlation is too low for the cost formula to be useful', 'Only 19% of the variation in maintenance cost is explained by machine hours', '81% of the variation in maintenance cost is explained by changes in machine hours',
   3, 'The coefficient of determination measures the proportion of total variation in the dependent variable (cost) explained by the independent variable (activity); here that proportion is 81%.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Which of the following is normally classified as an indirect material?',
   'Lubricants and small quantities of glue used in production', 'Lumber used by a furniture maker', 'Fabric used by a garment manufacturer', 'Steel plates used by a shipbuilder',
   0, 'Indirect materials are minor items that cannot be conveniently or economically traced to specific units, such as lubricants and glue; they are charged to factory overhead.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'The relevant range is best described as:',
   'The range of output over which total variable costs remain constant', 'The time period over which all costs become variable', 'The range of activity within which total fixed costs and the variable cost per unit remain constant', 'The range of sales between the breakeven point and full capacity',
   2, 'Cost behavior assumptions hold only within the relevant range: total fixed costs stay constant and the variable cost per unit is uniform within that band of activity.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'A mixed cost follows the formula Y = P50,000 + P12X, where X is units produced. At a volume of 10,000 units, the total cost per unit is:',
   'P5.00', 'P12.00', 'P17.00', 'P62.00',
   2, 'Total cost = P50,000 + (P12 × 10,000) = P170,000; per unit = P170,000 ÷ 10,000 = P17.00, consisting of P12 variable plus P5 of allocated fixed cost.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Which of the following is primarily a controllership function?',
   'Arranging bank loans and credit lines', 'Investing excess cash in marketable securities', 'Maintaining relationships with insurance underwriters', 'Reporting and interpreting financial results for management',
   3, 'The controller is the chief management accountant responsible for planning, reporting, and interpreting results; financing, investing, and insurance are treasurership functions.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'Which of the following is a discretionary fixed cost?',
   'Advertising and research costs set by an annual management decision', 'Depreciation on the factory building', 'Payments under a long-term lease contract', 'Real property taxes on the plant site',
   0, 'Discretionary fixed costs arise from annual management spending decisions and can be cut in the short run; depreciation, lease payments, and property taxes are committed fixed costs.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'A company reports direct materials P400,000, direct labor P250,000, variable factory overhead P150,000, fixed factory overhead P200,000, variable selling costs P100,000, and fixed administrative costs P120,000. Total product cost is:',
   'P800,000', 'P1,000,000', 'P1,100,000', 'P1,220,000',
   1, 'Product cost = DM + DL + all factory overhead = P400,000 + P250,000 + P150,000 + P200,000 = P1,000,000. Selling and administrative costs are period costs.', 3),
  ('MAS', 'Management Accounting Basics & Cost Behavior',
   'As production volume increases within the relevant range, which of the following occurs?',
   'Total fixed costs increase', 'Variable cost per unit increases', 'Fixed cost per unit remains constant', 'Total variable costs increase while fixed cost per unit decreases',
   3, 'Total variable cost rises in proportion to volume, while constant total fixed costs are spread over more units, reducing the fixed cost per unit.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'A product sells for P200 per unit and has variable costs of P120 per unit. The contribution margin per unit is:',
   'P80', 'P120', 'P200', 'P320',
   0, 'Contribution margin per unit = Selling price − Variable cost = P200 − P120 = P80.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'A product sells for P250 and has variable costs of P150 per unit. The contribution margin ratio is:',
   '37.5%', '66.7%', '60%', '40%',
   3, 'CM ratio = (P250 − P150) / P250 = P100 / P250 = 40%.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Fixed costs are P480,000 and the contribution margin per unit is P60. The breakeven point in units is:',
   '8,000 units', '7,200 units', '6,000 units', '9,600 units',
   0, 'Breakeven units = Fixed costs / CM per unit = P480,000 / P60 = 8,000 units.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Fixed costs total P540,000 and the contribution margin ratio is 45%. The breakeven point in pesos is:',
   'P243,000', 'P900,000', 'P1,200,000', 'P1,080,000',
   2, 'Breakeven pesos = Fixed costs / CM ratio = P540,000 / 0.45 = P1,200,000.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'A firm has fixed costs of P300,000, a unit selling price of P50, and a unit variable cost of P30. To earn a target operating profit of P120,000, the required sales in units is:',
   '6,000 units', '15,000 units', '21,000 units', '24,000 units',
   2, 'Required units = (Fixed costs + Target profit) / CM per unit = (P300,000 + P120,000) / (P50 − P30) = P420,000 / P20 = 21,000 units.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Fixed costs are P600,000 and the contribution margin ratio is 40%. To earn a target operating profit of P200,000, the required peso sales is:',
   'P2,000,000', 'P1,500,000', 'P500,000', 'P2,500,000',
   0, 'Required sales = (Fixed costs + Target profit) / CM ratio = (P600,000 + P200,000) / 0.40 = P800,000 / 0.40 = P2,000,000.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'A company wants an after-tax profit of P180,000 and is subject to a 25% tax rate. Fixed costs are P420,000 and the contribution margin per unit is P40. The required sales in units is:',
   '12,000 units', '15,000 units', '16,500 units', '17,250 units',
   2, 'Pre-tax target = P180,000 / (1 − 0.25) = P240,000. Required units = (P420,000 + P240,000) / P40 = P660,000 / P40 = 16,500 units.', 3),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'A firm targets an after-tax income of P150,000 at a 40% tax rate. Fixed costs are P500,000 and the CM ratio is 50%. Required peso sales equal:',
   'P1,300,000', 'P1,800,000', 'P1,600,000', 'P1,500,000',
   3, 'Pre-tax target = P150,000 / (1 − 0.40) = P250,000. Required sales = (P500,000 + P250,000) / 0.50 = P750,000 / 0.50 = P1,500,000.', 3),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Budgeted sales are P2,000,000 and breakeven sales are P1,400,000. The margin of safety in pesos is:',
   'P420,000', 'P600,000', 'P1,400,000', 'P3,400,000',
   1, 'Margin of safety = Budgeted sales − Breakeven sales = P2,000,000 − P1,400,000 = P600,000.', 1),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Sales are P3,000,000 and the margin of safety is P750,000. The margin of safety ratio is:',
   '20%', '25%', '75%', '80%',
   1, 'Margin of safety ratio = Margin of safety / Sales = P750,000 / P3,000,000 = 25%.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'At current sales, contribution margin is P900,000 and operating profit is P300,000. The degree of operating leverage is:',
   '0.33', '1.50', '3.00', '4.00',
   2, 'Degree of operating leverage = Contribution margin / Operating profit = P900,000 / P300,000 = 3.00.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'A company has a degree of operating leverage of 4.0. If sales increase by 12%, operating profit is expected to increase by:',
   '3%', '12%', '16%', '48%',
   3, 'Percentage change in profit = DOL × percentage change in sales = 4.0 × 12% = 48%.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Contribution margin is P1,200,000 and operating profit is P480,000. If sales decline by 10%, operating profit will:',
   'decrease by 10%', 'decrease by 2.5%', 'increase by 25%', 'decrease by 25%',
   3, 'DOL = P1,200,000 / P480,000 = 2.5. Change in profit = 2.5 × (−10%) = −25%, a decrease of 25%.', 3),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Products X and Y sell in a constant mix of 3:2 units. CM per unit is P30 for X and P50 for Y. The weighted-average contribution margin per unit of the mix is:',
   'P38', 'P40', 'P42', 'P80',
   0, 'Weighted CM = [(3 × P30) + (2 × P50)] / (3 + 2) = (P90 + P100) / 5 = P190 / 5 = P38.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'A firm sells products A and B in a 2:3 unit mix with CM per unit of P20 and P15, respectively. Fixed costs are P510,000. Total breakeven units (both products) equal:',
   '17,000 units', '25,500 units', '30,000 units', '34,000 units',
   2, 'Weighted CM = [(2 × P20) + (3 × P15)] / 5 = (P40 + P45) / 5 = P17. Total breakeven units = P510,000 / P17 = 30,000 units.', 3),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Currently selling price is P100, variable cost P60, and fixed costs P480,000. If selling price rises to P120 with no other change, the breakeven point in units will:',
   'rise to 12,000 units', 'fall to 6,000 units', 'stay at 12,000 units', 'fall to 8,000 units',
   3, 'Old BEP = P480,000 / (P100 − P60) = 12,000. New CM = P120 − P60 = P60; new BEP = P480,000 / P60 = 8,000 units.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Selling price is P80, variable cost P50, and fixed costs P360,000. If fixed costs increase by P90,000, the breakeven point in units will:',
   'decrease by 3,000 units', 'increase by 1,800 units', 'increase by 3,000 units', 'stay the same',
   2, 'Old BEP = P360,000 / P30 = 12,000. New BEP = P450,000 / P30 = 15,000. Increase = 3,000 units.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'A product currently has variable cost of P40 and sells for P100 with fixed costs of P420,000. If variable cost rises to P55, the new breakeven point in units is:',
   '7,000 units', '12,000 units', '10,500 units', '9,333 units',
   3, 'New CM = P100 − P55 = P45. New BEP = P420,000 / P45 = 9,333.33, rounded to 9,333 units.', 2),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Plan A has fixed costs of P200,000 and variable cost of P12 per unit; Plan B has fixed costs of P320,000 and variable cost of P8 per unit. The indifference point in units is:',
   '20,000 units', '65,000 units', '40,000 units', '30,000 units',
   3, 'Set total costs equal: P200,000 + P12Q = P320,000 + P8Q. P4Q = P120,000, so Q = 30,000 units.', 3),
  ('MAS', 'Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis',
   'Automated process: fixed costs P900,000, variable cost P5/unit. Manual process: fixed costs P300,000, variable cost P11/unit. Below the indifference volume, the manual process is cheaper. That indifference volume is:',
