   'Misstatements are both material and pervasive to the financial statements as a whole. The appropriate opinion is:',
   'A qualified opinion', 'An adverse opinion', 'A disclaimer of opinion', 'An unmodified opinion with emphasis of matter',
   1, 'When misstatements are material and pervasive, the financial statements as a whole are misleading, so the auditor expresses an adverse opinion.', 2),
  ('AUD', 'Audit Reports & Opinions',
   'The auditor is unable to obtain sufficient appropriate evidence about an account, and the possible effects of the undetected misstatements could be both material and pervasive. The appropriate opinion is:',
   'An adverse opinion', 'A qualified opinion', 'An unmodified opinion', 'A disclaimer of opinion',
   3, 'A scope limitation whose possible effects are material and pervasive precludes forming an opinion, so the auditor disclaims an opinion.', 2),
  ('AUD', 'Audit Reports & Opinions',
   'A scope limitation results in a possible misstatement that is material but not pervasive. The auditor should issue:',
   'A qualified (except for) opinion', 'A disclaimer of opinion', 'An adverse opinion', 'An unmodified opinion',
   0, 'A scope limitation that is material but not pervasive leads to a qualified opinion; pervasiveness would instead require a disclaimer.', 2),
  ('AUD', 'Audit Reports & Opinions',
   'An Emphasis of Matter paragraph in the auditors report is used to:',
   'Modify the opinion to qualified', 'Report a material misstatement', 'Draw users attention to a matter properly presented or disclosed that is fundamental to their understanding, without modifying the opinion', 'Substitute for a Key Audit Matter',
   2, 'An Emphasis of Matter paragraph highlights a matter appropriately presented or disclosed in the statements; it does not modify the auditors opinion.', 1),
  ('AUD', 'Audit Reports & Opinions',
   'The distinction between an Emphasis of Matter and an Other Matter paragraph is that an Other Matter paragraph refers to:',
   'A matter not presented or disclosed in the financial statements that is relevant to users understanding', 'A matter that is presented in the financial statements', 'A reason to qualify the opinion', 'A required Key Audit Matter',
   0, 'An Other Matter paragraph addresses something relevant to users that is not presented or disclosed in the statements, whereas Emphasis of Matter relates to something that is disclosed.', 2),
  ('AUD', 'Audit Reports & Opinions',
   'Under the corresponding figures approach to comparatives, the auditors opinion:',
   'Expresses a separate opinion on each period presented', 'Is always modified for the prior period', 'Refers to the current period only, with prior-period figures as an integral part of the current statements', 'Omits the prior period entirely',
   2, 'Under corresponding figures, prior-period amounts are part of the current-period statements and the opinion addresses the current period only, unlike comparative financial statements where each period gets an opinion.', 3),
  ('AUD', 'Audit Reports & Opinions',
   'Under PSA 720, the auditors responsibility with respect to other information in a document containing the audited financial statements is to:',
   'Express an audit opinion on the other information', 'Read the other information and consider whether it is materially inconsistent with the financial statements or the auditors knowledge', 'Ignore the other information entirely', 'Restate the other information',
   1, 'PSA 720 requires the auditor to read the other information and consider material inconsistencies or misstatements, but the auditor does not express an opinion or conclusion that provides assurance on it.', 2),
  ('AUD', 'Audit Reports & Opinions',
   'The date of the auditors report should be no earlier than the date on which the auditor has:',
   'Begun planning the engagement', 'Completed the interim testing', 'Delivered the engagement letter', 'Obtained sufficient appropriate evidence, including evidence that the financial statements have been approved by those with recognized authority',
   3, 'The report is dated no earlier than the date the auditor obtained sufficient appropriate evidence, including that all statements and notes were prepared and those with authority approved them.', 2),
  ('AUD', 'Audit Reports & Opinions',
   'The auditors report is ordinarily addressed to:',
   'The external legal counsel', 'Those for whom the report is prepared, often the shareholders or those charged with governance', 'The entitys bank only', 'The audit firms managing partner',
   1, 'Reports are addressed as required by the engagement circumstances, commonly to the shareholders or those charged with governance of the entity whose statements are audited.', 1),
  ('AUD', 'Audit Reports & Opinions',
   'An entity declines to capitalize a finance lease, instead expensing the payments, resulting in a misstatement the auditor judges material but confined to specific accounts and not pervasive. The auditor should issue:',
   'A qualified opinion describing the departure in the Basis for Qualified Opinion section', 'An adverse opinion', 'A disclaimer of opinion', 'An unmodified opinion with an Other Matter paragraph',
   0, 'A material but non-pervasive misstatement from a misapplication of the reporting framework warrants a qualified opinion, with the matter explained in the Basis for Qualified Opinion section.', 3)
)
insert into public.questions (topic_id, stem, choices, correct_index, explanation, difficulty)
select t.id, q.stem, jsonb_build_array(q.a, q.b, q.c, q.d), q.correct_index, q.explanation, q.difficulty
from q join t on t.code = q.subject_code and lower(t.name) = lower(q.topic)
where not exists (select 1 from public.questions x where x.stem = q.stem);

-- ===== tax-batch-001 =====
-- Generated from content/tax-batch-001.csv by scripts/csv-to-seed-sql.mjs — do not edit by hand.
-- Idempotent: skips any question whose stem already exists.
with t as (
  select tp.id, tp.name, s.code from public.topics tp
  join public.subjects s on s.id = tp.subject_id
),
q(subject_code, topic, stem, a, b, c, d, correct_index, explanation, difficulty) as (values
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Which statement best reflects the lifeblood doctrine?',
   'Taxes may be offset against the government''s unpaid obligations to the taxpayer', 'Courts may freely enjoin the collection of taxes upon a showing of inconvenience', 'The prompt and certain availability of taxes is essential because the government cannot continue to exist without revenue', 'The government is bound by the mistakes of its revenue officers under the principle of estoppel',
   2, 'Under the lifeblood doctrine, taxes are the lifeblood of the State and their prompt and certain availability is an imperious need. This is why collection generally cannot be enjoined, taxes are not subject to set-off, and the State is not estopped by errors of its agents.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Which of the three inherent powers of the State may also be exercised by public service companies and public utilities?',
   'Taxation', 'Eminent domain', 'Police power', 'All three inherent powers',
   1, 'Eminent domain may be delegated to and exercised by public service companies and public utilities. Taxation and police power are exercised only by the government or its political subdivisions.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'The BASIS of taxation, as distinguished from its theory, is:',
   'The reciprocal duties of protection by the State and support by its citizens', 'The principle that the existence of government is a necessity', 'The rule that taxes are the lifeblood of the nation', 'The doctrine that the power to tax involves the power to destroy',
   0, 'The basis of taxation is the benefits-protection theory: the citizen supports the State and the State protects the citizen. The theory of taxation, by contrast, is necessity or the lifeblood concept.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Under the canons of a sound tax system, fiscal adequacy means:',
   'Tax laws must be capable of convenient, just and effective administration', 'The tax burden must be proportionate to the taxpayer''s ability to pay', 'Tax rates must be identical in every province and city', 'Sources of revenue must be sufficient and elastic enough to meet the expanding expenditures of government',
   3, 'Fiscal adequacy requires that revenue sources, as a whole, be adequate and flexible enough to fund government needs. Choice A describes administrative feasibility and choice B describes theoretical justice.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Congress enacts a tax measure that proves extremely costly and burdensome for both the BIR and taxpayers to administer. Which is correct?',
   'The law is void for violating the principle of administrative feasibility', 'The law remains valid because administrative feasibility is a canon of a sound tax system, not a constitutional requirement', 'The law is void unless the Department of Finance certifies it as collectible', 'The law is automatically suspended until simplified regulations are issued',
   1, 'Non-observance of administrative feasibility, one of the canons of a sound tax system, does not by itself invalidate a tax law. Only violations of inherent or constitutional limitations render a tax law void.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Theoretical justice as a principle of a sound tax system requires that:',
   'The tax burden be proportionate to the taxpayer''s ability to pay', 'Revenue sources be elastic enough to fund all government programs', 'Tax laws be convenient and economical to administer', 'Taxes be collected exclusively from corporations with large profits',
   0, 'Theoretical justice means taxes must be based on the taxpayer''s ability to pay, echoing the constitutional directive to evolve a progressive system of taxation.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Which of the following is an INHERENT limitation on the power of taxation?',
   'No person shall be deprived of property without due process of law', 'No person shall be denied the equal protection of the laws', 'No law impairing the obligation of contracts shall be passed', 'Taxation may be exercised only within the territorial jurisdiction of the taxing authority',
   3, 'Territoriality is an inherent limitation that exists even without the Constitution. Due process, equal protection and non-impairment are constitutional limitations.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Which delegation of the taxing power is INVALID?',
   'Congress authorizes the President, within specified limits, to adjust tariff rates under the flexible tariff clause', 'The Constitution grants local government units the power to create their own sources of revenue', 'A statute authorizes the Secretary of Finance to select which businesses to tax and to fix the applicable tax rates', 'The BIR issues regulations prescribing the manner of filing returns under an existing tax law',
   2, 'The power to select the subjects of taxation and fix rates is purely legislative and cannot be delegated to an executive official. Tariff flexibility, local taxation and purely administrative implementation are recognized exceptions to non-delegation.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'The constitutional rule that taxation shall be uniform means:',
   'All taxpayers must pay exactly the same amount of tax', 'All subjects or objects belonging to the same class are taxed at the same rate', 'A single tax rate must apply nationwide to all kinds of income', 'Taxes must always be progressive in structure',
   1, 'Uniformity requires that persons or things belonging to the same class be taxed at the same rate; valid classification is allowed. It does not require equal amounts from every taxpayer.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'A religious order owns a building whose ground floor is leased to a commercial bakery while the upper floors are used as a convent. For real property tax purposes:',
   'Only the portion actually, directly and exclusively used for religious purposes is exempt; the leased ground floor is taxable', 'The entire building is exempt because the owner is a religious order', 'The entire building is taxable because part of it is used commercially', 'The building is exempt only if the rental income is donated to charity',
   0, 'The constitutional exemption attaches to actual, direct and exclusive USE of the property for religious, charitable or educational purposes, not to ownership. The portion leased out for commerce loses the exemption.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'A city imposes a local business tax on a store whose income is already subject to national income tax. The two impositions constitute:',
   'Direct double taxation, which is prohibited by the Constitution', 'Direct double taxation, which is nevertheless valid', 'No double taxation in any sense of the term', 'Indirect (broad sense) double taxation, which is not legally prohibited',
   3, 'Because the taxes are imposed by different taxing authorities (national government and city) and are different in kind, this is double taxation only in the broad sense, which is not prohibited. Direct double taxation requires the same subject, purpose, authority, jurisdiction, period and kind of tax.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Which of the following is NOT a method of mitigating or eliminating international double taxation?',
   'Entering into tax treaties with other states', 'Shifting the tax burden to consumers through higher prices', 'Allowing a tax credit for foreign taxes paid', 'Exempting income earned abroad from domestic tax',
   1, 'Tax treaties, foreign tax credits and exemption of foreign income are recognized relief measures against international juridical double taxation. Shifting merely transfers the economic burden and does not relieve double taxation.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'A city collects P500 from every bicycle-for-hire operator to fund a registry and periodic safety inspections, the amount approximating the cost of regulation. The exaction is:',
   'A tax, because it is collected by a local government', 'A toll, because it relates to the use of streets', 'A license fee imposed under the police power', 'A special assessment on personal property',
   2, 'An exaction imposed primarily for regulation, in an amount commensurate to the cost of regulation and supervision, is a license fee under the police power rather than a tax for revenue.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Which statement properly characterizes a special assessment?',
   'It is levied only on lands within the area benefited by a public improvement and is based on the special benefit received', 'It is a personal liability of the landowner even if the land receives no benefit', 'It is imposed on persons, property and business to raise general revenue', 'It is a periodic charge for the privilege of doing business',
   0, 'A special assessment is an enforced proportional contribution levied only on land, based wholly on the special benefit the land derives from a public improvement; it is not a personal liability and is not for general revenue.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'A corporation with a final and executory deficiency income tax assessment seeks to offset the assessment against the national government''s unpaid bill for goods the corporation delivered. May legal compensation take place?',
   'Yes, because both obligations are money claims that are due and demandable', 'Yes, provided the assessment has become final', 'Yes, but only with the approval of the Commission on Audit', 'No, because taxes are not contractual obligations and the government and the taxpayer are not mutual creditors and debtors of each other',
   3, 'Taxes arise from law, not contract, so the rules on legal compensation do not apply. The lifeblood doctrine bars set-off of taxes against ordinary claims against the government.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Which act constitutes tax EVASION rather than tax avoidance?',
   'Electing the 8% income tax option to legally lower the total tax due', 'Recording fictitious purchase invoices and deliberately underdeclaring sales', 'Deferring the perfection of a sale to the following taxable year', 'Claiming the optional standard deduction in lieu of itemized deductions',
   1, 'Evasion involves the use of illegal means, such as fictitious deductions and deliberate underdeclaration, coupled with intent to evade. The other choices are legal tax minimization (avoidance).', 1),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Faced with a higher excise tax, a manufacturer upgrades its machinery and recovers the tax through lower production costs without raising its selling price. This form of escape from taxation is:',
   'Shifting', 'Capitalization', 'Transformation', 'Evasion',
   2, 'Transformation occurs when the producer absorbs the tax and recovers it through more efficient production rather than passing it on. Shifting transfers the burden to buyers, while capitalization reduces the price of property purchased.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'A nonresident citizen granted a loan to a nonresident foreign corporation. The loan papers were signed in Manila and the interest was remitted to the lender''s Manila bank account. For Philippine income tax purposes, the interest is:',
   'Not taxable, because the situs of interest income is the residence of the debtor, which is abroad, and a nonresident citizen is taxed only on Philippine-source income', 'Taxable, because the creditor is a Filipino citizen', 'Subject to the 20% final withholding tax on interest', 'Taxable, because the contract was executed in Manila',
   0, 'Interest income is sourced at the residence of the DEBTOR. Since the debtor is a nonresident foreign corporation, the interest is foreign-source, and a nonresident citizen is taxed only on income from Philippine sources.', 3),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'A nonresident alien was paid a fee by a domestic corporation for consulting services performed entirely in Singapore. The fee is:',
   'Philippine-source income because the payor is a domestic corporation', 'Subject to the 25% final withholding tax on gross income', 'Subject to the graduated income tax rates', 'Foreign-source income not taxable to the nonresident alien, because compensation for services is sourced at the place of performance',
   3, 'The situs of income from services is the place where the services are performed, regardless of the payor''s residence or where payment is made. Services rendered abroad by a nonresident alien produce foreign-source income beyond Philippine taxing jurisdiction.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'On the retroactive application of tax laws, the general rule is that tax laws:',
   'Are always applied retroactively because taxes are the lifeblood of the State', 'Operate prospectively, unless the legislature clearly intends retroactivity and the retroactive application is not harsh or oppressive', 'May never be applied retroactively under any circumstance', 'Apply retroactively by default because they are civil in nature',
   1, 'Tax laws are applied prospectively as a rule. Retroactive application is permitted only when clearly provided by the legislature and provided it does not amount to a harsh, oppressive deprivation of due process.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'General Principles of Taxation',
   'Philippine internal revenue laws are properly characterized as:',
   'Penal in nature, because violations are punishable by imprisonment', 'Political in nature, because they are enacted by Congress', 'Civil in nature, which is why they remained effective even during enemy occupation', 'Criminal in nature, because the State prosecutes violators',
   2, 'Internal revenue laws are civil, not penal or political, in nature. Hence they continued in force during the enemy occupation of the Philippines and the rule against ex post facto laws does not generally apply to them.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A resident citizen earned compensation income in the Philippines and rental income from a condominium unit located in Singapore. Which income is subject to Philippine income tax?',
   'Only the Philippine compensation income', 'Only the Singapore rental income', 'Both the compensation and the rental income', 'Neither, because foreign income is always exempt',
   2, 'A resident citizen is taxable on income from all sources within and without the Philippines. Hence both the local compensation and the foreign rental income are taxable in the Philippines.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A non-resident citizen working as a seafarer on an ocean-going vessel earned salaries abroad and interest from a Philippine bank deposit. For Philippine income tax, the non-resident citizen is taxable on income from sources:',
   'Within and without the Philippines', 'Within the Philippines only', 'Without the Philippines only', 'Neither within nor without',
   1, 'A non-resident citizen (including a qualified seafarer) is taxable only on income derived from sources within the Philippines. The foreign salary is not taxed here, while the Philippine bank interest is.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A non-resident alien not engaged in trade or business in the Philippines received P500,000 of gross income from Philippine sources during the year. The income tax due is:',
   'P75,000', 'P40,000', 'P100,000', 'P125,000',
   3, 'A non-resident alien not engaged in trade or business is taxed at a flat final rate of 25% on gross income from Philippine sources. P500,000 x 25% = P125,000, with no deductions or personal exemptions allowed.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'Which of the following individuals is taxed using the graduated income tax table on net taxable income?',
   'A non-resident alien not engaged in trade or business in the Philippines', 'A domestic corporation', 'A non-resident citizen on income earned abroad', 'A non-resident alien engaged in trade or business in the Philippines',
   3, 'A non-resident alien engaged in trade or business in the Philippines is taxed on net taxable Philippine income using the graduated table. A non-resident alien not engaged in trade or business is taxed at 25% final on gross.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'An employee received during the year a 13th-month pay of P60,000 and other benefits totaling P45,000. Applying the P90,000 exclusion cap, how much of these benefits is included in taxable compensation income?',
   'P0', 'P15,000', 'P45,000', 'P105,000',
   1, 'The 13th-month pay and other benefits are excluded only up to P90,000. Total benefits = P60,000 + P45,000 = P105,000; the excess of P105,000 - P90,000 = P15,000 is included in taxable compensation.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'Which of the following amounts received by a rank-and-file employee is EXCLUDED from gross compensation income?',
   'Overtime pay of a regular employee', 'Commissions earned during the year', 'A productivity incentive bonus of P20,000 with no other benefits', 'Mandatory SSS, PhilHealth, and Pag-IBIG contributions withheld from salary',
   3, 'The employee share in mandatory SSS, PhilHealth, and Pag-IBIG contributions is excluded from gross compensation income. Overtime, commissions, and bonuses are generally taxable, subject only to the P90,000 benefits cap.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A statutory minimum wage earner received basic minimum wage plus overtime pay, holiday pay, night-shift differential, and hazard pay during the year. The income tax treatment is:',
   'The basic wage is exempt but the OT, holiday, night, and hazard pay are taxable', 'All of the items are taxable at graduated rates', 'Only the hazard pay is exempt', 'All of the items are exempt from income tax',
   3, 'A statutory minimum wage earner is exempt from income tax on the statutory minimum wage, and the exemption likewise covers holiday pay, overtime pay, night-shift differential pay, and hazard pay.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'Using the graduated table (0% up to P250,000; 15% over P250,000 to P400,000; 20% over P400,000 to P800,000; 25% over P800,000 to P2,000,000), a resident citizen has net taxable income of P650,000. The income tax due is:',
   'P72,500', 'P50,000', 'P82,500', 'P97,500',
   0, 'Tax on P400,000 = P22,500 (15% of P150,000). Excess P650,000 - P400,000 = P250,000 x 20% = P50,000. Total = P22,500 + P50,000 = P72,500.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'Using the graduated table (0% up to P250,000; 15% over P250,000 to P400,000; 20% over P400,000 to P800,000; 25% over P800,000 to P2,000,000; 30% over P2,000,000 to P8,000,000), a taxpayer has net taxable income of P1,200,000. The income tax due is:',
   'P190,000', 'P202,500', 'P240,000', 'P122,500',
   1, 'Tax on P800,000 = P102,500 (P22,500 + 20% of P400,000). Excess P1,200,000 - P800,000 = P400,000 x 25% = P100,000. Total = P102,500 + P100,000 = P202,500.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'Using the graduated table (cumulative tax on P8,000,000 is P2,202,500, then 35% on the excess over P8,000,000), a taxpayer has net taxable income of P10,000,000. The income tax due is:',
   'P2,902,500', 'P2,500,000', 'P3,500,000', 'P2,202,500',
   0, 'Tax on P8,000,000 = P2,202,500. Excess P10,000,000 - P8,000,000 = P2,000,000 x 35% = P700,000. Total = P2,202,500 + P700,000 = P2,902,500.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A self-employed professional with gross receipts of P2,400,000 (not VAT-registered, below the VAT threshold) elects the 8% income tax option. The income tax due under the 8% option is:',
   'P172,000', 'P192,000', 'P200,000', 'P150,000',
   0, 'The 8% option applies to gross sales or receipts in excess of P250,000 in lieu of graduated tax and the 3% percentage tax. (P2,400,000 - P250,000) x 8% = P2,150,000 x 8% = P172,000.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A purely self-employed individual (not VAT-registered, below the VAT threshold) has gross receipts of P1,000,000 and deductible expenses of P300,000. Under the graduated table, tax on the first P250,000 net is P0, 15% over P250,000 to P400,000, and 20% over P400,000 to P800,000. Comparing the graduated tax with the 8% option, the lower tax is:',
   'Graduated tax of P82,500', 'The 8% tax of P82,500', 'Graduated tax of P60,000', 'The 8% tax of P60,000',
   3, 'Net taxable income = P700,000; graduated tax = P22,500 + 20% of P300,000 = P82,500. The 8% option = (P1,000,000 - P250,000) x 8% = P60,000, which is lower.', 3),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A mixed-income earner has taxable compensation income of P500,000 and gross receipts from business of P800,000. He elects the 8% option on business income. In computing the 8% business tax, the P250,000 reduction:',
   'Is deducted from the gross receipts because every taxpayer gets it', 'Is NOT deducted because it is already incorporated in the graduated tax on compensation', 'Is deducted only from the compensation income', 'Is split equally between compensation and business',
   1, 'For a mixed-income earner electing 8% on business, the 8% is applied to the full gross sales or receipts WITHOUT the P250,000 reduction, since that amount is already built into the graduated rates applied to the compensation income.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A mixed-income earner elects 8% on business. His gross business receipts are P800,000 and he has no other business deductions. The 8% income tax on the business income is:',
   'P64,000', 'P44,000', 'P60,000', 'P40,000',
   0, 'For a mixed-income earner, the 8% is applied to gross receipts WITHOUT the P250,000 reduction. P800,000 x 8% = P64,000.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'Which condition must be satisfied before an individual may elect the 8% income tax option on gross sales or receipts?',
   'The taxpayer must be VAT-registered', 'Gross sales or receipts must exceed the P3,000,000 VAT threshold', 'The taxpayer must not be VAT-registered and must be below the P3,000,000 VAT threshold', 'The taxpayer must be a non-resident alien not engaged in trade or business',
   2, 'The 8% option is available only to non-VAT taxpayers whose gross sales or receipts do not exceed the P3,000,000 VAT threshold and who are not otherwise required to register for VAT or subject to other percentage taxes.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A resident citizen received P100,000 interest income from a Philippine peso bank deposit. The final tax to be withheld is:',
   'P20,000', 'P10,000', 'P15,000', 'P25,000',
   0, 'Interest income from a Philippine peso bank deposit of a resident citizen is subject to a 20% final withholding tax. P100,000 x 20% = P20,000.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A resident citizen earned P200,000 of royalties from a literary work (a published book). The final tax on this royalty is:',
   'P40,000', 'P10,000', 'P30,000', 'P20,000',
   3, 'Royalties on books, literary works, and musical compositions are subject to a reduced 10% final tax. P200,000 x 10% = P20,000, rather than the 20% rate that applies to other royalties.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A resident citizen received P150,000 of cash dividends from a domestic corporation. The final tax is:',
   'P15,000', 'P30,000', 'P22,500', 'P0',
   0, 'Cash dividends received by a citizen or resident from a domestic corporation are subject to a 10% final tax. P150,000 x 10% = P15,000.', 1),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'A resident citizen earned interest of P80,000 from a depository bank under the foreign currency deposit system (FCDU). The final tax is:',
   'P20,000', 'P16,000', 'P12,000', 'P8,000',
   2, 'Interest income of a resident from a foreign currency deposit (FCDU/EFCDU) is subject to a 15% final tax. P80,000 x 15% = P12,000.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'Which of the following passive income items earned by a resident citizen is NOT subject to a final withholding tax but is instead reported in the annual income tax return at graduated rates?',
   'Interest on a Philippine peso bank deposit', 'Royalties on a patent licensed to a local manufacturer', 'Net rental income from a commercial building', 'Cash dividends from a domestic corporation',
   2, 'Rental income is active or ordinary income reported in the annual return at graduated rates. Bank-deposit interest, royalties, and domestic dividends are subject to final withholding taxes.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'An individual sold a residential lot held as a capital asset for P5,000,000. The fair market value per the zonal valuation is P5,800,000 and the assessed value is P4,500,000. The capital gains tax is:',
   'P300,000', 'P290,000', 'P270,000', 'P348,000',
   3, 'The 6% capital gains tax on real property classified as a capital asset is based on the higher of the gross selling price and the fair market value (zonal or assessed). The highest is the zonal value of P5,800,000 x 6% = P348,000.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'An individual sold shares of stock of a domestic corporation (not traded through the local stock exchange) for P900,000. The shares were acquired for P500,000. The capital gains tax is:',
   'P60,000', 'P135,000', 'P24,000', 'P40,000',
   0, 'Sale of unlisted shares of a domestic corporation is subject to a 15% capital gains tax on the net capital gain. Net gain = P900,000 - P500,000 = P400,000; CGT = P400,000 x 15% = P60,000.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'An individual taxpayer held a capital asset (not real property or shares) for 18 months before selling it at a gain of P200,000. In computing taxable capital gains for an individual, the amount of gain to be reported is:',
   'P200,000', 'P100,000', 'P150,000', 'P0',
   1, 'For an individual, a capital asset held for more than 12 months is a long-term capital asset and only 50% of the gain or loss is taken into account. P200,000 x 50% = P100,000.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Individuals',
   'An individual taxpayer incurred a net capital loss of P50,000 in the prior year, when net income was positive. The net capital loss carryover may be deducted:',
