   1, 'An irrevocable trust is a separate taxpayer and computes its income tax using the graduated individual table, similar to an estate under judicial settlement.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Partnerships, Estates & Trusts',
   'Income of a revocable trust (where the grantor reserved the power to revest title in himself) is taxable to:',
   'The grantor', 'The trust as a separate entity', 'The beneficiary', 'No one, because it is exempt',
   0, 'Where the title to any part of the trust corpus may be revested in the grantor (a revocable trust), the income of that part is taxed to the grantor and not to the trust.', 2),
  ('TAX', 'Income Tax: Partnerships, Estates & Trusts',
   'A grantor created two trusts in favor of the same beneficiary. For income tax purposes, the income of the two trusts is:',
   'Consolidated and taxed as if it were the income of a single trust', 'Taxed separately, each enjoying its own exemption', 'Always taxed to the grantor', 'Exempt because there are multiple trusts',
   0, 'Where two or more trusts are created by the same grantor for the same beneficiary, the taxable income of all the trusts is consolidated and the tax computed as on a single trust, with any excess tax apportioned among the trustees.', 3)
