   'Yes, the deficiency is always recoverable like in a real mortgage', 'Yes, but only half of the deficiency', 'No, the sale extinguishes the principal obligation even if the proceeds fall short', 'No, and the pledgee must also refund the difference to the debtor',
   2, 'In pledge, if the proceeds of the public auction are less than the debt, the creditor is not entitled to recover the deficiency notwithstanding any contrary stipulation; conversely any excess belongs to the debtor unless otherwise stipulated.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Credit Transactions: Pledge, Mortgage & Guaranty',
   'In a real estate mortgage, ownership of the mortgaged immovable:',
   'Transfers to the mortgagee upon execution of the deed', 'Passes to the registry of deeds until the debt is paid', 'Is held jointly by mortgagor and mortgagee', 'Remains with the mortgagor, who only encumbers it as security',
   3, 'A real estate mortgage merely creates a real right and lien over the property; the mortgagor retains ownership and possession, and the mortgagee acquires only the right to foreclose upon default.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Credit Transactions: Pledge, Mortgage & Guaranty',
   'Carlo real estate mortgage is foreclosed and the auction proceeds are insufficient to cover the debt. May the mortgagee recover the deficiency?',
   'No, recovery of any deficiency is barred as in pledge', 'No, the mortgagee must keep silent and absorb the loss', 'Yes, but only if a chattel mortgage was also constituted', 'Yes, in a real estate mortgage the creditor may sue for the deficiency',
   3, 'Unlike pledge, a real estate mortgage allows the creditor to recover the deficiency after foreclosure, since mortgage law contains no rule extinguishing the balance.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Credit Transactions: Pledge, Mortgage & Guaranty',
