   2, 'A qualified indorsement (sans recourse / without recourse) makes the indorser a mere assignor of title and relieves her of the secondary liability to pay if the instrument is dishonored, though warranties remain.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'Which is a requisite for one to be a holder in due course?',
   'That the holder received it gratuitously after maturity', 'That the holder is the original payee only', 'That the holder took it in good faith and for value, complete and regular on its face, before maturity and without notice of any defect', 'That the holder notarized the instrument',
   2, 'A holder in due course must take an instrument complete and regular on its face, before maturity and without notice of prior dishonor, in good faith and for value, and without notice of any infirmity or defect in title.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'Under the shelter rule, a holder who is not himself a holder in due course but derives title through one:',
   'Can never enforce the instrument against personal defenses', 'Acquires the rights of a holder in due course, unless he was party to any fraud or illegality affecting the instrument', 'Must return the instrument to the original payee', 'Becomes a holder in due course in his own right for all purposes',
   1, 'The shelter rule lets a transferee who derives title through a holder in due course enjoy the latter rights, provided that transferee was not himself a party to any fraud or illegality affecting the instrument.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'Material alteration of a completed instrument is which kind of defense against a holder in due course?',
   'A purely personal defense that cannot be raised against anyone', 'A defense that voids the instrument entirely even for original tenor', 'No defense at all because alteration is always the maker fault', 'A real defense, but the holder in due course may enforce it according to its original tenor',
   3, 'Material alteration is a real defense; however, a holder in due course may still enforce the instrument according to its original tenor, recovering the amount as it stood before alteration.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'Which of the following is a REAL (absolute) defense available even against a holder in due course?',
   'Fraud in the inducement to sign', 'Failure of consideration', 'Want of delivery of a complete instrument', 'Minority of the maker, which is a defense available to the minor',
   3, 'Minority is a real defense available to the minor (rendering the obligation voidable as to him); fraud in inducement, failure of consideration, and want of delivery of a complete instrument are merely personal defenses.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'Ben fraudulently induces Ana to sign a note by misrepresenting its terms, then negotiates it to Carlo, a holder in due course. Against Carlo, Ana defense of fraud in inducement is:',
   'Unavailable, because fraud in the inducement is only a personal defense', 'Available, because all fraud is a real defense', 'Available only if Ana is a minor', 'Unavailable only if the note was post-dated',
   0, 'Fraud in the inducement is a personal defense that cannot be set up against a holder in due course; only fraud in factum (fraud as to the very character of the instrument) by a party without negligence is a real defense.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'Carlo delivers an INCOMPLETE and unsigned-as-to-amount note to Dina merely for safekeeping; she fills it in and negotiates it to a holder in due course. The defense of want of delivery of this incomplete instrument is:',
   'A personal defense usable only against ordinary holders', 'A real defense, so Carlo is not liable even to a holder in due course', 'No defense because incomplete instruments are void', 'A defense only against the immediate party',
   1, 'Want of delivery of an incomplete instrument is a real defense good even against a holder in due course; in contrast, want of delivery of a complete instrument is only a personal defense.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'The party primarily liable on a promissory note is the:',
   'Indorser', 'Maker', 'Drawer', 'Drawee before acceptance',
   1, 'On a promissory note the maker is primarily and absolutely liable to pay; on a bill, primary liability attaches to the drawee only once it accepts, becoming the acceptor.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'A general indorser, by indorsing, warrants among other things that:',
   'Nothing at all, since indorsement is gratuitous', 'That the maker is solvent forever', 'Only that he physically delivered the paper', 'The instrument is genuine, he has good title, prior parties had capacity, and the instrument is valid and subsisting',
   3, 'A general indorser warrants that the instrument is genuine and in all respects what it purports to be, that he has good title, that all prior parties had capacity to contract, and that the instrument is at the time valid and subsisting.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'Where a drawer signature on a check is forged, the general rule is that the drawee bank:',
   'Bears the loss and cannot charge the drawer account, since the forged drawer signature is wholly inoperative', 'May freely debit the drawer account because it acted in good faith', 'Shifts the loss to the last indorser in all cases', 'Recovers from the payee automatically',
   0, 'The drawee bank is generally bound to know its depositor signature; paying on a forged drawer signature, the bank bears the loss and cannot charge the drawer account, absent the drawer negligence or estoppel.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'When an indorsement on an order instrument is forged, as a general rule:',
   'Title passes normally to subsequent holders despite the forgery', 'The forged indorsement is merely a personal defense', 'No right to retain, discharge, or enforce payment can be acquired through the forged indorsement', 'Only the drawer, never the indorsers, bears the loss',
   2, 'A forged indorsement is wholly inoperative; no party can acquire the right to enforce payment through or under it, so parties after the forgery generally cannot enforce the instrument against those before it.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'Dina holds a check and, instead of the drawer, has it certified by the bank. The legal effect is that:',
   'Only the drawee bank is discharged', 'The drawer and all prior indorsers are discharged from liability', 'Nothing changes regarding the drawer liability', 'The check immediately becomes non-negotiable',
   1, 'Where the holder of a check procures it to be certified, the drawer and all prior indorsers are discharged from liability; certification at the holder request operates as the holder acceptance of the bank as sole obligor.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'Notice of dishonor to a party is dispensed with (excused) when:',
   'The holder simply forgets to send it', 'The drawer is a corporation', 'The instrument is for a small amount', 'The party to be notified is the very person who dishonored the instrument or notice cannot be given despite due diligence',
   3, 'Notice of dishonor may be excused, among other situations, when after due diligence it cannot be given, or where the party to be charged is the person who dishonored the instrument, such as a drawer who has no funds.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'A check presented for payment an unreasonable time after its issue is considered a stale check, the practical effect being that:',
   'The bank may refuse to pay it, and the holder may need to seek a replacement from the drawer', 'The drawer is automatically released from all liability on the underlying debt', 'The check becomes payable to bearer', 'The bank must still pay it regardless of how old it is',
   0, 'A check becomes stale when presented an unreasonable time after issue (commonly six months in banking practice); the drawee may, but is not obliged to, dishonor it, though the underlying obligation may persist.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'The crossing of a check (two parallel lines on its face) generally means that:',
   'The check has become non-negotiable and cannot be transferred', 'The check may be paid only through a bank, not over the counter in cash', 'The drawer signature has been canceled', 'The check must be paid in foreign currency',
   1, 'A crossed check serves as a warning that it must be deposited and collected through a bank rather than paid over the counter, alerting the holder to the limited purpose for which it may have been issued.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Negotiable Instruments',
   'A note promising payment on or before December 31, 2026 is payable at:',
   'An uncertain time, which destroys negotiability', 'A determinable future time, which does not impair negotiability', 'A time contingent on a condition, hence non-negotiable', 'The maker pleasure only',
   1, 'An instrument payable on or before a fixed date is payable at a determinable future time; this satisfies the requisite of certainty as to time and does not affect negotiability.', 2)
)
insert into public.questions (topic_id, stem, choices, correct_index, explanation, difficulty)
select t.id, q.stem, jsonb_build_array(q.a, q.b, q.c, q.d), q.correct_index, q.explanation, q.difficulty
from q join t on t.code = q.subject_code and lower(t.name) = lower(q.topic)
where not exists (select 1 from public.questions x where x.stem = q.stem);

-- ===== rfbt-batch-002 =====
-- Generated from content/rfbt-batch-002.csv by scripts/csv-to-seed-sql.mjs — do not edit by hand.
-- Idempotent: skips any question whose stem already exists.
with t as (
  select tp.id, tp.name, s.code from public.topics tp
  join public.subjects s on s.id = tp.subject_id
),
q(subject_code, topic, stem, a, b, c, d, correct_index, explanation, difficulty) as (values
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Andres and Bea contributed a parcel of land to their new partnership but signed only a private memorandum without any inventory of the property. What is the status of the partnership contract?',
   'Void, because contribution of immovable property requires a public instrument with an attached inventory signed by the parties', 'Valid and binding, since partnership is a consensual contract perfected by mere consent', 'Voidable at the option of either partner within four years', 'Unenforceable until ratified in writing by both partners',
   0, 'Under the Civil Code, when immovable property is contributed, the partnership contract must appear in a public instrument with an inventory of the property signed by the parties and attached; non-compliance renders the contract void.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Carla receives a regular share of the profits of Delos Santos Trading. Which circumstance prevents this profit-sharing from being treated as prima facie evidence that she is a partner?',
   'She agreed to share in the losses as well', 'She contributed money to the common fund', 'She received the share as installment payments of a debt owed to her', 'She participated in management decisions',
   2, 'The Civil Code lists exceptions where receipt of profits is not prima facie evidence of partnership, including profits received as payment of a debt by installments, as wages, as rent, as an annuity, or as interest on a loan.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Eduardo is an industrial partner in a construction firm. Which act is he prohibited from doing during the life of the partnership?',
   'Engaging only in a business of a different kind from that of the partnership', 'Lending money to the partnership at interest', 'Receiving a share of the profits', 'Engaging in any business for himself without the consent of the other partners',
   3, 'An industrial partner cannot engage in any business for himself unless the partnership expressly permits it; otherwise the capitalist partners may exclude him or avail of the benefits with damages.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Fe is a capitalist partner in a bakery. The capitalist partners are silent on competing ventures. Which business may Fe engage in for her own account?',
   'A business of a kind different from that of the partnership', 'Another bakery in the same city', 'Any food business including baking', 'No business at all during the partnership',
   0, 'A capitalist partner is prohibited only from engaging in the same line of business as the partnership; he may engage in a business of a different kind unless otherwise agreed.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'The partnership agreement of GHI is silent on profit sharing. Gloria contributed P300,000, Hector P100,000, and Ignacio served as industrial partner. How are profits distributed absent agreement?',
   'Equally among all three partners', 'Gloria and Hector equally, Ignacio nothing', 'Entirely to the capitalist partners in proportion to capital, with nothing for the industrial partner', 'The industrial partner receives a just and equitable share first, and the capitalist partners share in proportion to their capital contributions',
   3, 'Absent agreement, the industrial partner first receives such share as may be just and equitable, and the capitalist partners divide the remaining profits in proportion to their capital contributions.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'A stipulation in the articles of partnership excludes Jaime from any share in the profits while still requiring him to bear losses. What is the effect of this stipulation?',
   'The entire partnership contract is void', 'The stipulation is valid if Jaime consented in writing', 'The stipulation excluding him from profits is void, but the partnership itself remains valid', 'The stipulation merely makes the contract voidable',
   2, 'A stipulation excluding one or more partners from any share in the profits or losses is void, but the partnership contract subsists; the excluded matter is governed by the rules on profit and loss sharing.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Partnership KLM owes a trade creditor P900,000, but partnership assets are exhausted at P600,000. Kris and Leo are capitalist partners and Mario is the industrial partner. How is the P300,000 deficiency borne as to third persons?',
   'Only the capitalist partners Kris and Leo are liable to the creditor', 'Only Mario, as the managing partner, is liable', 'No partner is personally liable once partnership assets are exhausted', 'All partners, including the industrial partner Mario, are liable pro rata with their separate property to the creditor',
   3, 'To third persons, all partners including the industrial partner are liable pro rata with their separate property after partnership assets are exhausted; the industrial partner may, however, seek reimbursement from the capitalist partners under their internal loss-sharing arrangement.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Nora was never a partner but allowed Olivia to represent to a supplier that Nora was a member of OPQ Partnership, and Nora knew of and consented to it. The supplier extended credit relying on this. What is Nora liable as?',
   'A partner by estoppel, liable to the supplier as though she were an actual partner', 'Not liable, since she contributed no capital', 'Liable only for half the obligation', 'Liable only if she signed the credit agreement',
   0, 'One who by words or conduct represents himself, or consents to another representing him, as a partner is liable as a partner by estoppel to third persons who extend credit in reliance on the representation.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Which of the following is a cause that automatically dissolves a partnership by operation of law without need of any act of the partners?',
   'A disagreement among partners on policy', 'The death of any partner', 'The retirement of a salaried employee', 'A temporary decline in profits',
   1, 'Dissolution occurs by operation of law upon the death of any partner, insolvency of a partner or the partnership, civil interdiction of a partner, or when a specific event makes the business unlawful, among others.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Upon liquidation of RST Partnership, after partnership assets are realized, in what order are the liabilities ranked for payment?',
   'Capital first, then outside creditors, then profits', 'Those owing to outside creditors, then those owing to partners other than for capital and profits, then capital, then profits', 'Partner advances first, then outside creditors, then capital', 'Profits first, then capital, then outside creditors',
   1, 'The Civil Code ranks liabilities in liquidation as: first, those owing to creditors other than partners; second, those owing to partners other than for capital and profits (advances); third, those owing to partners for capital; and last, those owing to partners for profits.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'In a limited partnership, Ulysses is a limited partner whose surname appears in the partnership name. What is the consequence?',
   'The partnership name is void', 'He loses his entire contribution', 'He becomes liable as a general partner to creditors who did not know he was only a limited partner', 'Nothing, since limited partners may freely use their surnames',
   2, 'A limited partner whose surname appears in the partnership name is liable as a general partner to partnership creditors who extend credit without actual knowledge that he is only a limited partner, subject to the exceptions in the law.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Which act regarding partnership property generally requires the unanimous consent of all the partners?',
   'Entering into ordinary contracts of sale of merchandise', 'Hiring an ordinary employee', 'Paying a routine utility bill', 'Any act of alteration of immovable property contributed to the partnership',
   3, 'While each partner is an agent for acts in the ordinary course of business, an act that alters immovable property of the partnership requires the unanimous consent of all the partners.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Partner Vicente, without authority and against the express prior agreement of all partners, sold partnership inventory to a buyer who had no knowledge of the restriction. Is the partnership bound?',
   'Yes, the partnership is bound because the act was apparently for carrying on its business in the usual way and the buyer was in good faith', 'No, the sale is void in all cases', 'No, because the other partners did not consent', 'Yes, but only up to Vicente''s capital share',
   0, 'An act of a partner apparently carrying on the partnership business in the usual way binds the partnership, even contrary to a private restriction, unless the third person had knowledge of the lack of authority.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Two persons orally agreed to form a partnership to engage in general trading with combined cash contributions of P5,000. They executed no document at all. Is a juridical personality created?',
   'No, because partnerships always require registration with the SEC to exist', 'Yes, the partnership acquires juridical personality distinct from the partners even without a written instrument', 'No, because the contributions are below the statutory minimum capital', 'Yes, but only after one year of operation',
   1, 'A partnership has a juridical personality separate and distinct from each partner from the moment of the meeting of the minds; no writing or registration is required for juridical personality where no immovable property is contributed.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Industrial partner Wendy was compelled to pay a partnership creditor from her own funds because partnership assets were insufficient. As between the partners, what is her right?',
   'She must absorb the payment as her share of the losses', 'She may demand double the amount as a penalty', 'She is entitled to reimbursement from the capitalist partners, since an industrial partner is exempt from losses among the partners', 'She loses her right to future profits',
   2, 'Although the industrial partner is liable to third persons, as among the partners he is exempt from losses; thus he is entitled to reimbursement from the capitalist partners for amounts he paid to creditors.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Partner Xander, a managing partner appointed in the articles of partnership, is sought to be removed by the other partners who together hold the controlling interest. What vote and ground are required?',
   'He may be removed at any time without cause by a simple majority', 'He may not be removed during the life of the partnership', 'He may be removed only by unanimous vote and any cause', 'He may be removed only for a just and lawful cause by the vote of the partners holding the controlling interest',
   3, 'A managing partner appointed in the articles of partnership may be removed only for just and lawful cause and by the vote of the partners owning the controlling interest; if appointed after the partnership is constituted, he may be removed even without cause.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Partnership Law',
   'Yolanda assigned her entire interest in the profits of YZ Partnership to her creditor Zenaida. What right does Zenaida acquire?',
   'Full rights as a substitute partner including management', 'The right to receive the profits to which Yolanda would otherwise be entitled, but not to interfere in management or inspect the books', 'The right to demand immediate dissolution', 'No right at all, since partnership interests are non-assignable',
   1, 'A conveyance by a partner of her interest does not make the assignee a partner; the assignee is merely entitled to receive the profits the assigning partner would otherwise receive and cannot interfere in management or require accounts.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Under RA 11232, what is the permissible range in the number of incorporators of a stock corporation, other than a One Person Corporation?',
   'Five to eleven', 'One to fifteen', 'Five to fifteen', 'Two to fifteen',
   1, 'The Revised Corporation Code allows one to fifteen incorporators, who may be natural persons, partnerships, associations, or corporations; a single stockholder may form a One Person Corporation.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Maria organized a corporation but the law does not require a minimum capital stock for her line of business. What is the rule on minimum capital under the RCC?',
   'Stock corporations are generally not required to have a minimum capital stock unless a special law provides otherwise', 'At least twenty-five percent of authorized capital must always be P25,000', 'A minimum paid-up capital of P5,000 is always required', 'A minimum subscribed capital of P50,000 is mandatory',
   0, 'The RCC removed the general minimum capital stock requirement; stock corporations need not have a minimum capital stock except as specifically provided by special law or regulation.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Absent any contrary provision in its articles of incorporation, what is the corporate term of a corporation organized under the RCC?',
   'Fifty years, renewable once', 'Perpetual existence', 'Twenty years, renewable indefinitely', 'Thirty years, non-renewable',
   1, 'Under the RCC, a corporation has perpetual existence unless its articles of incorporation provide otherwise; corporations existing prior to the RCC are also deemed to have perpetual term unless they elect to retain a fixed term.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'The board of Bayanihan Corp wishes to extend the corporate term. What stockholder approval is required in addition to majority board approval?',
   'A simple majority of the outstanding capital stock', 'Unanimous approval of all stockholders', 'No stockholder vote, only board approval', 'The vote of stockholders representing at least two-thirds of the outstanding capital stock',
   3, 'Extension or shortening of the corporate term requires approval by a majority of the board and the vote of stockholders representing at least two-thirds of the outstanding capital stock, with appraisal rights available to dissenters.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Five friends operated a business as a corporation, but their articles were never validly filed due to a fatal defect, though they acted in good faith under color of a valid incorporation. How are they best characterized?',
   'A de jure corporation in all respects', 'A corporation by estoppel only', 'A de facto corporation, whose existence may be questioned only by the State in a direct proceeding', 'A general partnership with no corporate attributes',
   2, 'A de facto corporation exists where there is a valid law, a bona fide attempt to incorporate, and actual use of corporate powers; its existence may be attacked only by the State through quo warranto, not collaterally by private parties.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Several persons misrepresented their group as a corporation to a supplier and incurred debts though no incorporation was ever attempted. When the supplier sues, what doctrine prevents them from denying corporate existence to escape liability?',
   'Corporation by estoppel, under which those assuming to act as a corporation are liable as general partners', 'De facto corporation doctrine', 'The trust fund doctrine', 'The doctrine of separate juridical personality',
   0, 'Persons who assume to act as a corporation knowing it to be without authority are liable as general partners; one who deals with them as a corporation is estopped, and they are likewise estopped from denying corporate existence to avoid liability.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'The directors of Sampaguita Inc caused the corporation to assume an obligation purely to benefit a director personally, draining corporate funds to defraud creditors. A court is asked to disregard the corporate fiction. This remedy is known as:',
   'Quo warranto', 'The business judgment rule', 'Ultra vires nullification', 'Piercing the veil of corporate fiction',
   3, 'Piercing the veil of corporate fiction allows courts to disregard the separate personality where it is used to defeat public convenience, justify wrong, protect fraud, or defend crime, holding the responsible persons liable.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'What is the term of office of directors and of trustees, respectively, under the RCC?',
   'Directors one year and trustees three years', 'Both one year', 'Both three years', 'Directors three years and trustees one year',
   0, 'Directors of stock corporations are elected for a term of one year, while trustees of non-stock corporations serve for a term of three years, with staggered terms so that approximately one-third are elected annually.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Roberto owns 1,000 shares in a corporation electing five directors. Applying cumulative voting, what is the maximum number of votes he may cast for a single nominee?',
   '1,000 votes', '500 votes', '5,000 votes', '25,000 votes',
   2, 'Under cumulative voting, a stockholder may multiply his shares by the number of directors to be elected and cast all such votes for one candidate; 1,000 shares times 5 directors equals 5,000 votes for a single nominee.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'A corporation vested with public interest must have independent directors. Who is an independent director under the RCC?',
   'Any director who owns less than five percent of shares', 'A person who, apart from shareholdings and fees, is independent of management and free from any relationship that could materially interfere with independent judgment', 'A director appointed by the SEC', 'The corporate secretary',
   1, 'An independent director is one who, apart from shareholdings and fees received, is independent of management and free from any business or other relationship that could materially interfere with the exercise of independent judgment.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Which combination of officer qualifications is correct under the RCC?',
   'The president need not be a director but must be a citizen', 'The president must be a director, the treasurer must be a resident of the Philippines, and the secretary must be a citizen and resident of the Philippines', 'The treasurer must be a director and a citizen', 'The secretary must be a director and a resident',
   1, 'Under the RCC, the president must be a director; the treasurer must be a resident of the Philippines; and the corporate secretary must be both a citizen and a resident of the Philippines.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Director Lorna learned of a business opportunity that belonged to the corporation but took it for herself, profiting personally. Under the corporate opportunity doctrine, what is her obligation?',
   'She may keep the profit because directors owe no duty regarding outside opportunities', 'She must merely disclose the opportunity afterward with no liability', 'She forfeits her shares automatically', 'She must account to the corporation for all profits, unless her act is ratified by the vote of stockholders representing two-thirds of the outstanding capital stock',
   3, 'A director who acquires for himself a business opportunity that should belong to the corporation must account for the profits by refunding them, unless the act is ratified by stockholders owning two-thirds of the outstanding capital stock.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Which corporate act requires only the approval of a majority of the board together with the vote or written assent of stockholders representing two-thirds of the outstanding capital stock?',
   'Increase of the authorized capital stock', 'Declaration of cash dividends', 'Filling of an ordinary vacancy in the board not due to expiration of term', 'Adoption of an ordinary contract in the usual course of business',
   0, 'Increasing or decreasing the capital stock, incurring bonded indebtedness, selling all or substantially all assets, investing in another business, and similar major acts require board majority plus stockholders representing two-thirds of the outstanding capital stock.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'A corporation has paid-in capital of P10,000,000 and retained earnings of P12,000,000 with no justified reason to retain the surplus. What is the maximum it may retain without violating the RCC?',
   'P12,000,000, since there is no limit on retained earnings', 'P10,000,000, since retained earnings in excess of 100 percent of paid-in capital must generally be declared as dividends', 'P5,000,000, equal to half the paid-in capital', 'Nothing, all earnings must be distributed',
   1, 'Stock corporations are prohibited from retaining surplus profits in excess of 100 percent of paid-in capital, subject to exceptions such as definite corporate expansion projects, loan covenants, or special circumstances justifying retention.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Treasury shares reacquired by a corporation are held in its name. What is their status as to voting and dividends?',
   'They retain full voting and dividend rights', 'They have voting rights but no dividend rights', 'They have no voting rights and are not entitled to dividends while held in the treasury', 'They have dividend rights but no voting rights',
   2, 'Treasury shares are shares previously issued and fully paid but subsequently reacquired by the corporation; while held in the treasury they have no voting rights and earn no dividends because they are not considered outstanding.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'In a delinquency sale of subscribed but unpaid shares, who is declared the winning bidder?',
   'The bidder who offers the highest cash price per share', 'The bidder who offers to pay the full balance due plus costs for the smallest number of shares', 'The bidder willing to take the largest number of shares', 'The first registered bidder regardless of price',
   1, 'In a delinquency sale, the highest bidder is the person willing to pay the full amount of the balance due plus accrued interest, costs, and expenses for the smallest number of shares, with the remaining shares credited to the delinquent stockholder.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'On what matter may holders of non-voting shares nonetheless vote under the RCC?',
   'On the sale of all or substantially all of the corporate property and assets', 'On the election of the regular board of directors', 'On the approval of ordinary management contracts', 'On the declaration of cash dividends',
   0, 'Non-voting shares may still vote on certain fundamental matters, including amendment of the articles, sale of all or substantially all assets, incurring bonded indebtedness, merger or consolidation, increase or decrease of capital, investment in another corporation, and dissolution.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'No-par value shares of a stock corporation under the RCC may not be issued for a consideration of less than what amount per share?',
   'One peso', 'Ten pesos', 'Five pesos', 'No floor exists',
   2, 'No-par value shares may not be issued for a consideration less than five pesos per share, and the entire consideration received constitutes capital not available for dividend distribution.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'A proxy was executed without a stated period of effectivity. For how long is such a proxy valid under the RCC?',
   'Five years from execution', 'It is valid only for the meeting for which it was intended', 'One year regardless of the meeting', 'Indefinitely until revoked',
   1, 'A proxy is valid only for the meeting for which it was intended unless otherwise provided; in no case may a proxy be valid and effective for a period longer than five years at any one time.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Two corporations undergo a merger. After the merger takes effect, what happens to the liabilities of the absorbed corporation?',
   'The liabilities are extinguished by operation of law', 'The surviving corporation assumes all the liabilities and obligations of the absorbed corporation', 'The liabilities become the personal obligations of the former directors', 'The liabilities must be separately assumed by written novation',
   1, 'In a merger, the surviving corporation possesses all the rights and properties and assumes all the liabilities and obligations of the constituent corporations as though it had incurred them itself.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'After a corporation is dissolved, for how long does it continue as a body corporate for the purpose of winding up its affairs?',
   'Five years from dissolution', 'One year from dissolution', 'Three years from dissolution', 'Indefinitely until all assets are distributed',
   2, 'A dissolved corporation continues as a body corporate for three years after dissolution for the purpose of prosecuting and defending suits, settling affairs, disposing of property, and distributing assets, but not to continue its business.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Which statement about a One Person Corporation under the RCC is correct?',
   'It must have at least two incorporators', 'It is not required to have a minimum authorized capital stock unless a special law requires it, and the single stockholder is by default its sole director and president', 'Banks and pre-need companies may freely incorporate as OPCs', 'It is required to submit and file corporate bylaws',
   1, 'An OPC is not required to have a minimum capital stock unless otherwise provided by law, need not submit bylaws, and its single stockholder is by default the sole director and president; banks, insurance, pre-need, and similar entities cannot form OPCs.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'An emergency board action is needed because a quorum of directors cannot be assembled and there is an imminent grave danger to the corporation. Who may be designated to act?',
   'Any stockholder appointed by the SEC', 'The corporate secretary acting alone', 'A court-appointed receiver', 'A temporary director chosen from among the officers, by unanimous vote of the remaining directors, limited to the emergency action',
   3, 'Under the RCC, when a vacancy prevents a quorum and there is an emergency requiring immediate action, the remaining directors may unanimously designate an officer as a temporary director to act only for the specific emergency action.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'A stockholder seeks to inspect the corporate books. The corporation refuses, claiming the request is for an improper purpose. Who bears the burden, and what is the consequence of unjustified refusal?',
   'The stockholder must obtain a court order before any inspection', 'The corporation bears the burden of proving the improper purpose, and an officer who unjustifiably refuses may be held liable for damages and penalties', 'The stockholder bears the burden of proving a proper purpose in all cases', 'Inspection may be refused for any reason at the board''s discretion',
   1, 'The right of inspection is broad; when refusal is challenged, the corporation has the burden of proving that the stockholder acted in bad faith or for an illegitimate purpose, and unjustified refusal exposes responsible officers to liability.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'A voting trust agreement is executed transferring shares to a trustee. What is the maximum period for which such an agreement may be effective under the RCC, absent a specific exception?',
   'Three years', 'Ten years', 'Five years at any one time', 'Perpetual',
   2, 'A voting trust agreement may not exceed five years at any one time, except when made a condition in a loan agreement, in which case it may last for the duration of the loan.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'A corporation amends its articles of incorporation. When does the amendment take effect?',
   'Immediately upon board approval alone', 'Upon publication in a newspaper of general circulation', 'Upon approval by the SEC, or if not acted upon within six months from filing for a cause not attributable to the corporation, from the date of filing', 'Upon the next annual stockholders meeting',
   2, 'An amendment to the articles of incorporation takes effect upon approval by the SEC, or if not acted upon within six months from the date of filing for a cause not attributable to the corporation, from the date of filing.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Distinguish the vote required to amend the articles of incorporation from the vote to amend the bylaws (without a delegated power to the board).',
   'Both require two-thirds of the outstanding capital stock', 'Articles require two-thirds of the outstanding capital stock, while bylaws require a majority of the outstanding capital stock', 'Both require a majority of the outstanding capital stock', 'Articles require a majority and bylaws require two-thirds',
   1, 'Amendment of the articles of incorporation requires majority board approval and the vote of stockholders owning two-thirds of the outstanding capital stock, whereas amendment of bylaws requires majority board approval and a majority of the outstanding capital stock.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'Redeemable shares were issued by a corporation. Which statement is correct about them?',
   'They may never be redeemed if it would impair capital, in all cases', 'They are the same as treasury shares from issuance', 'They may be purchased or taken up by the corporation upon the expiration of a fixed period regardless of the existence of unrestricted retained earnings, if so provided', 'They always carry mandatory voting rights',
   2, 'Redeemable shares may be purchased by the corporation upon the expiration of a fixed period as stated in the articles and certificate, even without unrestricted retained earnings, provided the corporation has sufficient assets to cover debts and liabilities after redemption.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Revised Corporation Code',
   'A minority stockholder sues in the corporation''s name to redress a wrong done to the corporation, after the board refused to act. This action is a:',
   'Individual suit', 'Representative suit', 'Class suit for personal injury', 'Derivative suit',
   3, 'A derivative suit is brought by a stockholder on behalf of and for the benefit of the corporation to redress a wrong committed against it, where the board itself fails or refuses to sue; any recovery accrues to the corporation.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'Because an insurance contract is generally prepared by the insurer with terms the insured merely adheres to, any ambiguity in the policy is construed:',
   'In favor of the insurer', 'Against the insurer that drafted it', 'Strictly against the insured', 'Liberally in favor of forfeiture',
   1, 'An insurance policy is a contract of adhesion; its ambiguous provisions are interpreted strictly against the insurer who prepared the contract and liberally in favor of the insured to effect coverage.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'Ramon takes out a life insurance policy on his own life. To what extent must he show insurable interest?',
   'His interest in his own life is unlimited, so no pecuniary measure is required', 'He must prove a pecuniary interest equal to the face amount', 'He must show he has dependents', 'He has no insurable interest in his own life',
   0, 'Every person has an unlimited insurable interest in his own life and may insure it for any amount; the requirement of a pecuniary or measurable interest applies when insuring the life of another.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'Sofia insures the life of her business debtor in whom she has a pecuniary interest. When must this insurable interest exist?',
   'At the time of death only', 'At the time the policy takes effect, but it need not exist at the time of the insured''s death', 'At both inception and death', 'At no particular time',
   1, 'In life insurance, insurable interest must exist when the policy takes effect but need not exist at the time of loss or death; in property insurance, the interest must exist both at inception and at the time of loss.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'Teresa insured her warehouse against fire. She sold the warehouse before it burned down. May she recover on the fire policy?',
   'Yes, because the policy was valid at inception', 'Yes, because she paid all premiums', 'No, because property policies are never assignable', 'No, because in property insurance insurable interest must exist both when the policy attaches and when the loss occurs',
   3, 'In property insurance, the insured must have an insurable interest both at the time the insurance takes effect and at the time of the loss; having parted with ownership before the fire, Teresa cannot recover.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'Under the general rule on premium payment in non-life insurance, when does the insurer become liable?',
   'Upon mere agreement to insure even without premium payment', 'Sixty days after the policy is issued regardless of payment', 'Only after the first loss occurs', 'Only upon actual payment of the premium, under the cash-and-carry principle, subject to recognized exceptions',
   3, 'The general rule is cash-and-carry: no policy is valid and binding unless the premium is paid, subject to exceptions such as a grace period in life insurance, a credit term granted, estoppel, or a written acknowledgment of receipt of premium.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'Applicant Ulrich failed to disclose a material fact he knew, which the insurer would have considered in fixing the premium or accepting the risk. This is:',
   'Concealment, which entitles the injured party to rescind the contract', 'A mere innocent representation with no effect', 'A breach of warranty curable by tender', 'Permissible because there was no fraud',
   0, 'Concealment is the neglect to communicate that which a party knows and ought to communicate; whether intentional or unintentional, concealment of a material fact entitles the injured party to rescind the contract.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'A life insurance policy has been in force for more than two years during the insured''s lifetime. The insurer later discovers a concealment. May it still rescind on that ground?',
   'Yes, concealment always voids the policy regardless of time', 'Yes, but only within five years', 'No, the incontestability clause bars the insurer from rescinding for concealment or misrepresentation after the policy has been in force for two years during the insured''s lifetime', 'No, only if the premiums were fully paid',
   2, 'Under the incontestability clause, after a life insurance policy has been in force during the lifetime of the insured for at least two years, the insurer can no longer rescind on the ground of concealment or misrepresentation, except for excepted defenses like non-payment of premiums.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'Victor named his sister as beneficiary in his life policy without stating that the designation is irrevocable. What is the legal presumption?',
   'The designation is revocable, so Victor may change the beneficiary without the sister''s consent', 'The designation is irrevocable and cannot be changed', 'The designation is void for lack of insurable interest', 'The sister must consent before any premium is paid',
   0, 'Unless the insured expressly waives the right to revoke, the designation of a beneficiary is presumed revocable, allowing the insured to change the beneficiary without the latter''s consent.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'Wilma insured the same building against the same fire risk with three different insurers for the same interest. This situation is:',
   'Reinsurance, which is valid only with the insured''s consent', 'Over-insurance that automatically voids all the policies', 'Double insurance, where the insured may recover only up to the actual loss, with insurers contributing pro rata', 'Co-insurance that doubles the recoverable amount',
   2, 'Double insurance exists when the same person is insured by several insurers separately for the same subject and interest; the insured cannot recover more than the actual loss, and the insurers share the loss pro rata.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'After paying a fire claim, the insurer of Xavier seeks to step into his rights against the third party whose negligence caused the fire. This right is:',
   'Reinsurance, requiring a separate contract', 'Available in life insurance as well', 'Barred because the insured was paid in full', 'Subrogation, which arises by operation of law upon payment in property insurance',
   3, 'Upon payment of a property loss, the insurer is subrogated to the rights of the insured against the wrongdoer to the extent of the indemnity paid; subrogation does not apply to life insurance, which is not a contract of indemnity.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'An insured peril and an excepted peril concur to cause a loss. Under the doctrine of proximate cause, when is the insurer liable?',
   'When the proximate cause of the loss is the peril insured against, even if a remote cause is excepted', 'Whenever any contributing cause is covered', 'Only when the excepted peril is wholly absent', 'Never, if any excepted peril is present in the chain',
   0, 'The insurer is liable when the proximate or efficient cause of the loss is a peril insured against; a remote excepted cause does not defeat recovery if the immediate efficient cause is covered.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'Yolly, the insured under a life policy, intentionally took her own life one month after the policy was issued, and the policy contained no suicide clause extending coverage. What is the general rule?',
   'The insurer is always liable for suicide regardless of timing', 'The insurer is not liable where the insured commits suicide within the period the law or policy allows the insurer to deny the claim and there was no insanity', 'Suicide voids the policy in all circumstances', 'The beneficiary recovers only the premiums paid',
   1, 'As a rule, the insurer is liable when suicide is committed after the policy has been in force for two years, or is committed in a state of insanity; otherwise, where the loss is the willful act of the insured, the insurer is not liable.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Insurance Code',
   'Insurer Alpha cedes part of a risk it underwrote to Insurer Beta. As to the original insured, what is the nature of this arrangement?',
   'It is double insurance binding the insured', 'It transfers the insured''s claim directly to Beta', 'It is reinsurance, a contract between insurers to which the original insured is not a party and on which he has no claim against the reinsurer', 'It requires the insured''s prior written consent to be valid',
   2, 'Reinsurance is a contract by which one insurer insures the risk it has assumed with another insurer; it is independent of the original policy, and the original insured has no interest in or right of action under the reinsurance contract absent stipulation.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'A promoter offers investors a scheme where they contribute money to a common enterprise and expect profits solely from the efforts of the promoter. Under the Howey test as applied to the SRC, this is:',
   'Not a security because no stock certificate is issued', 'A simple loan exempt from regulation', 'An investment contract, which is a security subject to registration', 'A commercial paper outside SEC jurisdiction',
   2, 'An investment contract exists where there is an investment of money in a common enterprise with the expectation of profits primarily from the efforts of others; it is a security under the SRC and is subject to registration unless exempt.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'Which of the following is an exempt transaction under the SRC that does not require registration of the securities?',
   'The sale of securities to fewer than twenty persons in the Philippines during any twelve-month period', 'An initial public offering to the general public', 'The continuous public sale of securities through a broker', 'Any sale of shares of a listed company',
   0, 'Among exempt transactions are isolated transactions, the distribution of stock dividends, and sales to fewer than twenty persons in the Philippines during any twelve-month period (private placement), which do not require registration.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'Two traders enter matched buy and sell orders for the same security at the same time to create a misleading appearance of active trading. This prohibited practice is:',
   'Legitimate market making', 'A permissible block trade', 'A bona fide tender offer', 'A manipulative device involving matched orders or wash sales',
   3, 'Wash sales and matched orders involve transactions that create a false or misleading appearance of active trading or of the market for a security; they are prohibited manipulative practices under the SRC.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'A corporate insider possesses material nonpublic information about his company. Under the SRC, what must he do before trading in the company''s securities?',
   'Trade immediately before the information becomes public', 'Disclose the information to the public or abstain from trading', 'Inform only the board of directors', 'Obtain SEC clearance for each trade',
   1, 'An insider in possession of material nonpublic information must either disclose it to the investing public or abstain from trading; trading while in possession of such information constitutes prohibited insider trading.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'Mandatory tender-offer rules under the SRC are triggered when a person intends to acquire what level of equity in a public company?',
   'At least ten percent at any time', 'Any acquisition of voting shares', 'At least thirty-five percent of the outstanding equity in a twelve-month period, or an acquisition that results in ownership of more than fifty percent', 'Only a one hundred percent buyout',
   2, 'A mandatory tender offer is required when a person intends to acquire at least thirty-five percent of outstanding equity securities in a public company within a twelve-month period, or such percentage that results in ownership of more than fifty percent of the total outstanding equity.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'Under the Cooperative Code (RA 9520), what is the minimum number of natural persons required to organize a primary cooperative?',
   'At least five natural persons', 'At least three natural persons', 'At least twenty natural persons', 'At least fifteen natural persons',
   3, 'A primary cooperative may be organized by at least fifteen natural persons who are Filipino citizens, of legal age, with a common bond of interest, and it must register with the Cooperative Development Authority to acquire juridical personality.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'In a primary cooperative, how is voting power allocated among members?',
   'One member, one vote, regardless of the number of shares held', 'In proportion to the number of shares held', 'By the amount of patronage during the year', 'By seniority of membership',
   0, 'A fundamental cooperative principle is democratic control: in a primary cooperative each member is entitled to only one vote regardless of shareholdings, distinguishing it from a stock corporation.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'Under RA 9520, what is the maximum share capital that a single member may hold in a cooperative?',
   'Not more than fifty percent', 'Not more than ten percent of the share capital of the cooperative', 'No limit applies', 'Not more than twenty-five percent',
   1, 'To preserve the cooperative character and prevent control by a few, no member may own or hold more than ten percent of the share capital of the cooperative.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'From the net surplus of a cooperative, which statutory fund must receive an allocation of at least ten percent?',
   'The reserve fund', 'The patronage refund fund', 'The optional fund only', 'Interest on share capital',
   0, 'The Cooperative Code requires that the net surplus be apportioned to statutory funds: at least ten percent to the reserve fund, an amount to the education and training fund, an optional fund, and the balance to interest on share capital and patronage refunds.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'A cooperative seeks to enjoy tax exemption under RA 9520. Which condition is generally relevant to that exemption?',
   'Earning profits exclusively from non-members', 'Maintaining a minimum of one hundred members', 'Compliance with registration and the cooperative''s transactions, with accumulated reserves and undivided net savings within the limits set by law', 'Listing its shares on the stock exchange',
   2, 'Duly registered cooperatives dealing principally with members enjoy tax exemptions; the extent depends on compliance with the Code, including limits on accumulated reserves and undivided net savings as provided by law and regulations.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'Shares of a listed company are sold by a stockholder directly to a single buyer in a one-time, isolated transaction not in the ordinary course of a securities business. This is best characterized under the SRC as:',
   'A public offering requiring a prospectus', 'Insider trading', 'A mandatory tender offer', 'An exempt transaction that does not require registration',
   3, 'An isolated transaction in which there is no public offering and the seller is not engaged in the business of selling securities is an exempt transaction under the SRC and does not require registration.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'An audit of a duly registered cooperative must be conducted by:',
   'Any auditor chosen by the chairperson alone', 'An external auditor accredited by the Cooperative Development Authority', 'Only the Commission on Audit', 'An auditor accredited solely by the SEC',
   1, 'Cooperatives are required to have their financial statements audited by an independent external auditor accredited by the Cooperative Development Authority to ensure compliance and proper accounting of funds.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Securities Regulation & Cooperatives',
   'Aling Rosa subscribes to shares in a primary cooperative and later acquires more shares than other members, expecting added voting power. Under RA 9520, can additional shares increase her voting power?',
   'No, because each member in a primary cooperative has only one vote regardless of the number of shares owned', 'Yes, votes are proportional to shareholdings', 'Yes, but only up to ten votes', 'No, because members are not allowed to own shares at all',
   0, 'In a primary cooperative the principle of one member, one vote applies; voting power is not tied to the number of shares, so acquiring more shares does not give Aling Rosa greater voting power.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'Under RA 1405, peso bank deposits are generally absolutely confidential. Which of the following is a recognized exception allowing examination?',
   'Upon mere request of any creditor of the depositor', 'Whenever the BIR wishes to verify income for assessment', 'Upon written permission of the depositor, in cases of impeachment, upon court order in bribery or dereliction of duty by public officials, or where the deposit is the subject matter of litigation', 'Upon request of a private employer',
   2, 'RA 1405 makes peso deposits absolutely confidential except: upon written permission of the depositor; in cases of impeachment; upon order of a competent court in cases of bribery or dereliction of duty of public officials; and when the deposit is the subject matter of litigation, among other statutory exceptions.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'Compared with peso deposits, foreign-currency deposits under RA 6426 enjoy a narrower set of exceptions. What is the principal exception to their confidentiality?',
   'Disclosure only upon the written permission or consent of the depositor', 'Disclosure upon order of any trial court', 'Disclosure to any government agency on request', 'Disclosure whenever a civil case is filed',
   0, 'RA 6426 provides that foreign-currency deposits are confidential and may not be examined except upon the written permission or consent of the depositor; the exceptions are far narrower than those under RA 1405 for peso deposits.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'Under the AMLA as amended, what cash transaction with a covered bank in one banking day is a covered transaction that must be reported?',
   'A transaction in cash or other equivalent monetary instrument exceeding five hundred thousand pesos in one banking day', 'Any transaction exceeding ten thousand pesos', 'Only transactions exceeding one million pesos', 'Only transactions involving foreign currency',
   0, 'For banks and similar covered institutions, a covered transaction is one in cash or other equivalent monetary instrument exceeding P500,000 within one banking day; this is separate from suspicious transactions, which have no threshold.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'A casino single-transaction in cash with a customer triggers a covered transaction report under the AMLA when it exceeds what amount?',
   'Five hundred thousand pesos', 'Five million pesos', 'Seven million five hundred thousand pesos', 'One million pesos',
   1, 'For casinos as covered persons, the covered transaction threshold is a single cash transaction exceeding P5,000,000 or its equivalent, distinct from the P500,000 threshold applicable to banks.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'A real estate developer covered by the AMLA completes a single cash sale. Above what amount does it become a covered transaction subject to reporting?',
   'Five hundred thousand pesos', 'Five million pesos', 'Seven million five hundred thousand pesos', 'One million pesos',
   2, 'Real estate developers and brokers are covered persons under the AMLA for single cash transactions exceeding P7,500,000, distinguishing the threshold from those applicable to banks and casinos.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'A transaction has no minimum amount yet must still be reported because it has no clear economic justification and may relate to an unlawful activity. This is:',
   'A covered transaction requiring the P500,000 threshold', 'An exempt transaction', 'A suspicious transaction, which has no threshold amount', 'A DOSRI transaction',
   2, 'Suspicious transactions must be reported regardless of amount when circumstances such as no underlying legal or economic justification, unusual structuring, or links to unlawful activity are present; unlike covered transactions, they have no threshold.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'Under the AMLA, which court issues a freeze order over monetary instruments related to an unlawful activity, and for how long initially?',
   'The Regional Trial Court, for up to one year', 'The Supreme Court, for ninety days', 'The AMLC itself, indefinitely', 'The Court of Appeals, for a period not exceeding twenty days, extendable up to a maximum of six months',
   3, 'Upon ex parte application by the AMLC, the Court of Appeals may issue a freeze order effective for a period not exceeding twenty days, which the court may extend upon proper showing up to a maximum of six months.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'Maria maintains a single deposit account with Bank A holding P1,300,000 when the bank is closed. What is the maximum PDIC deposit insurance she can claim?',
   'One million pesos', 'One million three hundred thousand pesos', 'Five hundred thousand pesos', 'The full amount plus accrued interest',
   0, 'Effective March 2025, the PDIC maximum deposit insurance coverage is P1,000,000 per depositor per bank; amounts in excess of the maximum are not insured and are treated as ordinary claims against the closed bank.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'Which of the following is NOT insured by the PDIC?',
   'A peso savings deposit', 'An investment product such as a unit investment trust fund and deposits payable abroad', 'A peso time deposit', 'A peso demand deposit',
   1, 'PDIC insures deposits but excludes investment products such as bonds, securities, and trust accounts, as well as deposits that are unfunded, fictitious, or payable in a foreign country; only qualified deposits are covered up to the maximum.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'Pedro issued a check that was dishonored for insufficient funds. When does the disputable presumption of knowledge of insufficiency arise under BP 22?',
   'Immediately upon issuance of the check', 'Only after a criminal complaint is filed', 'When he fails to pay the amount or make arrangements within five banking days after receiving written notice of dishonor', 'After thirty days from the date of the check',
   2, 'Under BP 22, the presumption of knowledge of insufficient funds arises upon dishonor and the drawer''s failure to pay the holder the amount due or make arrangements for payment within five banking days after receiving written notice of dishonor.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'How is the offense under BP 22 best characterized, and what is the consequence of that characterization?',
   'It is malum in se, requiring proof of intent to defraud', 'It requires actual damage to the payee', 'It is a purely civil obligation', 'It is malum prohibitum, so the mere act of issuing a worthless check that is dishonored is punishable regardless of intent to defraud',
   3, 'BP 22 punishes the act of making or issuing a worthless check as malum prohibitum; criminal intent or deceit is not an element, distinguishing it from estafa, which requires fraud or deceit as an essential element.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'A corporate treasurer signed a company check that later bounced for insufficient funds. Who may be held criminally liable under BP 22?',
   'The corporation itself, which may be imprisoned', 'The person who actually signed the check on behalf of the corporation', 'Only the company president regardless of who signed', 'No one, since a corporation cannot commit a crime',
   1, 'Where the check is drawn by a corporation, the person who actually signed the check on its behalf is the one held criminally liable under BP 22, since a juridical entity cannot be imprisoned but its signatory can.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Banking Laws, AMLA, PDIC & BP 22',
   'Spouses Reyes maintain a joint and or account with P1,600,000 in a single bank that is later closed. How is PDIC insurance generally applied to this joint account?',
   'The joint account is insured up to a maximum of P1,000,000, separate from any individually owned accounts of each spouse', 'Each spouse is separately insured up to P1,000,000 for the joint account, totaling P2,000,000', 'The account is not insured because it is jointly owned', 'The account is insured for the full P1,600,000',
   0, 'PDIC treats a joint account as insured up to the P1,000,000 maximum for that account, with the insured amount generally divided among co-owners; this coverage is separate from any single accounts each depositor maintains in the same bank.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'Under RA 8792, an electronic document offered as evidence:',
   'Is never admissible because it is not on paper', 'Is admissible only if notarized', 'Has the legal effect, validity, and enforceability of a written document and is admissible in evidence', 'Has only persuasive, not evidentiary, value',
   2, 'The Electronic Commerce Act adopts the functional-equivalent approach, giving electronic documents and electronic signatures the same legal effect, validity, and enforceability as their paper counterparts, and they are admissible in evidence.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'An online merchant requires that a contract be in writing and signed. Under RA 8792, when is an electronic signature deemed to satisfy a signature requirement?',
   'Only when accompanied by a wet-ink specimen', 'When a method is used to identify the party and indicate his approval of the electronic document, and that method is reliable and appropriate', 'Only when issued by a government certification authority', 'Never, because signatures must be handwritten',
   1, 'An electronic signature satisfies a legal signature requirement when a method is used to identify the person and indicate his access to or approval of the electronic document, and the method is as reliable as appropriate given the circumstances.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'Under the Data Privacy Act (RA 10173), which of the following is classified as sensitive personal information?',
   'An individual''s business email address', 'A company''s registered trade name', 'Information about an individual''s health, genetic, or sexual life', 'A publicly listed corporate office address',
   2, 'Sensitive personal information includes data about race, ethnic origin, marital status, age, color, religious or political affiliations, health, education, genetic or sexual life, government-issued identifiers, and proceedings for offenses, requiring heightened protection.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'Following a personal data breach involving sensitive personal information likely to result in serious harm, within what period must the National Privacy Commission and affected data subjects generally be notified?',
   'Within thirty days', 'Within fifteen days', 'Within seventy-two hours upon knowledge of or reasonable belief that the breach occurred', 'Only upon demand by the data subject',
   2, 'The Data Privacy Act and its rules require notification to the National Privacy Commission and affected data subjects within seventy-two hours upon knowledge of, or reasonable belief that, a personal data breach requiring notification has occurred.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'A company collects and decides the purposes for processing customers'' personal data, while a separate IT firm processes the data only on the company''s instructions. Under RA 10173, what are they respectively?',
   'Both are personal information controllers', 'The company is the personal information controller and the IT firm is the personal information processor', 'Both are personal information processors', 'The IT firm is the controller and the company is the processor',
   1, 'A personal information controller controls the collection, holding, processing, or use of personal data and determines the purposes; a personal information processor processes personal data only on behalf of, and as instructed by, the controller.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'Which data-subject right under RA 10173 allows an individual to obtain a copy of his personal data in an electronic or structured format and to transmit it to another controller?',
   'The right to be forgotten only', 'The right to lodge a complaint', 'The right to object to direct marketing only', 'The right to data portability',
   3, 'The right to data portability gives the data subject the right to obtain from the controller a copy of his data in a commonly used, electronic, or structured format that allows further use, including transfer to another controller.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'A retailer posts a sign reading no return, no exchange on all purchased items. Under the Consumer Act (RA 7394), this practice is:',
   'A prohibited deceptive sales act, because consumers retain rights against defective goods', 'Lawful, since the consumer is forewarned', 'Permissible only for discounted items', 'Allowed if the sign is conspicuously displayed',
   0, 'A blanket no-return, no-exchange policy is a prohibited deceptive practice because it misleads consumers into believing they have waived their statutory rights against defective or non-conforming goods; consumers retain warranty and remedy rights.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'Under the price-tag rule of the Consumer Act, a retailer must:',
   'Display prices only upon a customer''s request', 'Charge a price higher than the tagged price if costs rose', 'Indicate the price of consumer products in an appropriate tag, label, or marking, and may not sell above the displayed price', 'Round prices to the nearest hundred pesos',
   2, 'The price-tag rule requires that consumer products be clearly priced through tags, labels, or markings, and prohibits selling at a price higher than that stated, protecting consumers from arbitrary pricing.', 1),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'Under the IP Code (RA 8293), to be patentable, an invention must satisfy which set of requirements?',
   'Mere usefulness alone', 'Novelty, inventive step, and industrial applicability', 'Registration with the BIR', 'Commercial success in the market',
   1, 'A patentable invention must be new (novelty), involve an inventive step that is not obvious to a person skilled in the art, and be industrially applicable; certain subject matter such as discoveries and scientific theories is non-patentable.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'Under RA 8293, a registered trademark is protected for an initial period, after which it may be renewed. What is that period and a key maintenance requirement?',
   'Twenty years from filing, non-renewable', 'Fifty years from registration', 'Ten years, renewable for ten-year periods, with a required declaration of actual use', 'Life of the owner plus fifty years',
   2, 'A certificate of trademark registration is valid for ten years and is renewable for periods of ten years, but the registrant must file a declaration of actual use within the prescribed periods, or the mark is removed from the register.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'E-Commerce, Data Privacy, Consumer Protection & IP',
   'Under RA 8293, when does copyright protection over an original literary or artistic work arise, and how long do economic rights generally last?',
   'Only upon registration, lasting twenty years', 'From publication, lasting ten years renewable', 'From deposit with the National Library, lasting indefinitely', 'From the moment of creation, with economic rights lasting during the life of the author plus fifty years after death',
   3, 'Copyright subsists from the moment of creation of the original work, without need of registration; for most works, economic rights endure during the life of the author and for fifty years after his death.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insolvency (FRIA) & Other Regulatory Laws',
   'Under RA 10142, when is a debtor considered insolvent?',
   'Only when a court has declared it bankrupt', 'When the debtor is generally unable to pay its liabilities as they fall due in the ordinary course of business, or has liabilities greater than its assets', 'Whenever it incurs a single overdue debt', 'Only when all its checks have bounced',
   1, 'FRIA defines insolvency as the financial condition of a debtor that is generally unable to pay its liabilities as they fall due in the ordinary course of business, or has liabilities that are greater than its assets.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insolvency (FRIA) & Other Regulatory Laws',
   'An individual debtor possesses sufficient property to cover his debts but foresees the impossibility of meeting them when they fall due. What remedy under FRIA fits this situation?',
   'Liquidation', 'Involuntary rehabilitation', 'Suspension of payments', 'Cross-border insolvency proceedings',
   2, 'Suspension of payments is available to an individual debtor who possesses sufficient property to cover all his debts but foresees the impossibility of meeting them when they respectively fall due, allowing a deferment or restructuring of payment.', 2),
  ('RFBT', 'Insolvency (FRIA) & Other Regulatory Laws',
   'Upon issuance of a Commencement Order in a rehabilitation proceeding, a Stay or Suspension Order is included. Which claim is generally NOT covered by the suspension?',
   'Collection suits by ordinary creditors against the debtor', 'Enforcement of judgments against the debtor''s property', 'A claim against a surety or other person solidarily liable with the debtor, who is not himself under rehabilitation', 'Foreclosure proceedings against the debtor''s mortgaged assets',
   2, 'The Stay Order suspends enforcement of claims against the debtor, but it does not extend to claims against sureties and other persons solidarily liable with the debtor who are not themselves under rehabilitation, so creditors may proceed against them.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Insolvency (FRIA) & Other Regulatory Laws',
   'Despite the objection of a class of creditors, the rehabilitation court may approve and bind all creditors to a rehabilitation plan if it meets statutory standards. This judicial authority is called:',
   'The stay order', 'The cram-down power', 'The right of subrogation', 'The trust fund doctrine',
   1, 'FRIA grants the court the cram-down power to approve a rehabilitation plan and bind dissenting creditors over their objection, provided the plan complies with the statutory requirements and is feasible and fair.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Insolvency (FRIA) & Other Regulatory Laws',
   'An out-of-court or informal restructuring agreement under FRIA, once it complies with the standstill requirements, imposes a standstill period among the parties of how long?',
   'Sixty days', 'Thirty days', 'Two hundred forty days', 'One hundred twenty days',
   3, 'Under FRIA, a standstill period agreed upon by the parties to an out-of-court or informal restructuring is binding, and the law contemplates a standstill period not exceeding one hundred twenty days, subject to the required approvals and publication.', 3),
  ('RFBT', 'Insolvency (FRIA) & Other Regulatory Laws',
   'In a liquidation proceeding under FRIA, after the Liquidation Order, how are the assets of the insolvent debtor distributed among creditors?',
   'In accordance with the rules on concurrence and preference of credits under the Civil Code', 'Equally among all creditors regardless of the nature of their claims', 'To the creditor who first filed a claim, in full', 'Entirely to the government before any private creditor',
   0, 'Upon liquidation, the liquidator converts the debtor''s assets to cash and distributes the proceeds to creditors following the rules on concurrence and preference of credits under the Civil Code, which rank preferred, secured, and ordinary credits.', 3)
)
insert into public.questions (topic_id, stem, choices, correct_index, explanation, difficulty)
select t.id, q.stem, jsonb_build_array(q.a, q.b, q.c, q.d), q.correct_index, q.explanation, q.difficulty
from q join t on t.code = q.subject_code and lower(t.name) = lower(q.topic)
where not exists (select 1 from public.questions x where x.stem = q.stem);

